WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.856 align:middle line:90%


00:00:05.856 --> 00:00:09.272 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:09.272 --> 00:00:27.605 align:middle line:90%


00:00:27.605 --> 00:00:29.230 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA MEREDITH:
An increasing number

00:00:29.230 --> 00:00:31.090 align:middle line:10%
of parents around the
world are struggling

00:00:31.090 --> 00:00:34.200 align:middle line:10%
to contend with a diagnosis
of autism in the family.

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:36.610 align:middle line:84%
If you ask what causes it,
you'll get as many questions

00:00:36.610 --> 00:00:39.010 align:middle line:84%
as answers, which is
what happened to Rupert

00:00:39.010 --> 00:00:41.000 align:middle line:90%
Isaacson and his wife, Kristin.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.230 align:middle line:84%
They took matters, however,
into their own hands

00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:46.490 align:middle line:84%
when their son, Rowan, was
diagnosed, packed their bags,

00:00:46.490 --> 00:00:49.190 align:middle line:84%
and headed to Mongolia to meet
with some of the world's most

00:00:49.190 --> 00:00:50.630 align:middle line:90%
remote shaman.

00:00:50.630 --> 00:00:52.543 align:middle line:84%
Let's take a peek
at their journey.

00:00:52.543 --> 00:00:54.760 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:00:54.760 --> 00:00:59.320 align:middle line:84%
-In April, 2004, my son, Rowan,
was diagnosed with autism.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:01.505 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAMING]

00:01:01.505 --> 00:01:05.620 align:middle line:10%
The feeling was like being hit
across the face with a baseball

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:07.960 align:middle line:10%
bat.

00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:10.640 align:middle line:10%
Our lives became cloaked under
a mountain of conflicting

00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:12.425 align:middle line:10%
information on the disorder.

00:01:12.425 --> 00:01:14.010 align:middle line:90%
We tried everything.

00:01:14.010 --> 00:01:16.270 align:middle line:90%
He didn't speak to us.

00:01:16.270 --> 00:01:19.060 align:middle line:84%
One day, he ran away
from me and ran right up

00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:21.490 align:middle line:90%
to a horse school Betsy.

00:01:21.490 --> 00:01:23.610 align:middle line:84%
The moment I put
Rowan on Betsy's back,

00:01:23.610 --> 00:01:25.280 align:middle line:90%
he began to speak.

00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:27.770 align:middle line:90%
-He's a nice horse.

00:01:27.770 --> 00:01:30.610 align:middle line:84%
-As Rowan began to open up
to me for the first time,

00:01:30.610 --> 00:01:32.440 align:middle line:90%
a light bulb went on in my head.

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:37.870 align:middle line:84%
Was there a place on earth that
combined healing with horses?

00:01:37.870 --> 00:01:39.520 align:middle line:90%
Mongolia.

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:42.360 align:middle line:84%
This is a story about
how, as a family,

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:44.810 align:middle line:84%
we did something
crazy, how we ended up

00:01:44.810 --> 00:01:47.853 align:middle line:84%
going halfway across the
world in search of a miracle.

00:01:47.853 --> 00:01:58.600 align:middle line:90%


00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:01.350 align:middle line:84%
-I think it wasn't exactly
Rowan's vision of Mongolia.

00:02:01.350 --> 00:02:04.550 align:middle line:84%
-We're going to go up a
several-thousand-foot mountain

00:02:04.550 --> 00:02:06.440 align:middle line:84%
and perform a four-hour
ritual with shamans.

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:08.150 align:middle line:90%
Isn't that what all families do?

00:02:08.150 --> 00:02:11.426 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:02:11.426 --> 00:02:12.589 align:middle line:90%


00:02:12.589 --> 00:02:14.380 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes I think he'
like leaping forward,

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:15.328 align:middle line:90%
and sometimes it's like he's--

00:02:15.328 --> 00:02:16.266 align:middle line:90%
-I know.

00:02:16.266 --> 00:02:17.224 align:middle line:90%
- --totally regressing.

00:02:17.224 --> 00:02:20.070 align:middle line:90%


00:02:20.070 --> 00:02:21.910 align:middle line:84%
I couldn't help
wondering, did I really

00:02:21.910 --> 00:02:23.810 align:middle line:84%
have his best interest
at heart here?

00:02:23.810 --> 00:02:25.534 align:middle line:84%
-I don't know how
useful it is to think

00:02:25.534 --> 00:02:28.754 align:middle line:84%
of us as normal and
Rowan as the sick one.

00:02:28.754 --> 00:02:33.220 align:middle line:90%


00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:34.590 align:middle line:90%
-And then something happened.

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:37.390 align:middle line:90%
Rowan began laughing, giggling.

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:39.250 align:middle line:84%
We were together
again as a family.

00:02:39.250 --> 00:02:42.722 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:02:42.722 --> 00:03:03.058 align:middle line:90%


00:03:03.058 --> 00:03:05.370 align:middle line:84%
His autism forced
me to listen to what

00:03:05.370 --> 00:03:07.330 align:middle line:90%
interested him above all else.

00:03:07.330 --> 00:03:08.693 align:middle line:90%
We're onto something good here.

00:03:08.693 --> 00:03:09.526 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:03:09.526 --> 00:03:11.580 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, this isn't
your typical response

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:14.980 align:middle line:84%
to a diagnosis of autism
in the family for sure.

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:17.770 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we're not suggesting to
anyone they have to pack it in,

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:19.600 align:middle line:84%
get on a horse, ride
eight hours a day

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:21.840 align:middle line:84%
into the wilderness to
find these remote shaman,

00:03:21.840 --> 00:03:22.640 align:middle line:90%
but you did.

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:23.400 align:middle line:90%
>>RUPERT ISAACSON: We did.

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:25.274 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you learned
a tremendous amount

00:03:25.274 --> 00:03:28.640 align:middle line:84%
through that process and
probably even more since then,

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:30.430 align:middle line:90%
and I'd like to-- I don't know.

00:03:30.430 --> 00:03:32.930 align:middle line:84%
I want to precede this even,
because you and I were talking

00:03:32.930 --> 00:03:37.120 align:middle line:84%
off camera, and it just struck
me about you and your child,

00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:37.920 align:middle line:90%
Rowan.

00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:39.090 align:middle line:84%
What a beautiful
boy, by the way.

00:03:39.090 --> 00:03:39.790 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Thank you.

00:03:39.790 --> 00:03:40.990 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Beautiful boy.

00:03:40.990 --> 00:03:45.940 align:middle line:84%
And you were raised in London
as part of the public school

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:49.350 align:middle line:84%
system, which, in our
parlance, is the private school

00:03:49.350 --> 00:03:53.250 align:middle line:84%
system, which is
really almost-- I mean,

00:03:53.250 --> 00:03:57.150 align:middle line:84%
you couldn't have a
more polarized reality

00:03:57.150 --> 00:03:59.610 align:middle line:84%
as two little boys
between you and your son.

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:01.140 align:middle line:90%
What a divide.

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:05.600 align:middle line:84%
And what had to be brought up
in you to contend with your son,

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:08.290 align:middle line:84%
and just share a little bit
about your own background

00:04:08.290 --> 00:04:09.496 align:middle line:90%
growing up in this way.

00:04:09.496 --> 00:04:11.370 align:middle line:10%
>>ISAACSON: Well, I have
a hybrid background,

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:16.290 align:middle line:10%
and I think that's always
been my main strength that I

00:04:16.290 --> 00:04:18.610 align:middle line:10%
could draw on.

00:04:18.610 --> 00:04:20.210 align:middle line:10%
Mongrel vigor.

00:04:20.210 --> 00:04:21.209 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mongrel vigor.

00:04:21.209 --> 00:04:22.760 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yes.

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:25.200 align:middle line:84%
I have an interesting
background.

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:26.380 align:middle line:90%
My mother is South African.

00:04:26.380 --> 00:04:27.650 align:middle line:90%
My father is Zimbabwean.

00:04:27.650 --> 00:04:30.330 align:middle line:90%
I was born and raised in the UK.

00:04:30.330 --> 00:04:32.610 align:middle line:84%
On my father's side,
which is Russian Jews,

00:04:32.610 --> 00:04:34.610 align:middle line:90%
who went to Africa.

00:04:34.610 --> 00:04:36.940 align:middle line:84%
On my mother's side were
Africanas and English

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:40.350 align:middle line:84%
who went to Africa in
the late 17th century.

00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:43.790 align:middle line:84%
And we're very much part of
the problem of apartheid,

00:04:43.790 --> 00:04:45.942 align:middle line:84%
but we're also people who
fought against apartheid,

00:04:45.942 --> 00:04:47.150 align:middle line:90%
and were in jail fighting it.

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:48.858 align:middle line:84%
So I came from a very
politicized family,

00:04:48.858 --> 00:04:52.842 align:middle line:84%
but I grew up in England
looking at this stuff.

00:04:52.842 --> 00:04:55.300 align:middle line:84%
Am I part of that, or am I part
of England, or what or what

00:04:55.300 --> 00:04:55.610 align:middle line:90%
or what?

00:04:55.610 --> 00:04:58.110 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Oh, you were part of
the class that are considered

00:04:58.110 --> 00:04:59.780 align:middle line:90%
the masters of the universe.

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:02.033 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Well,
only by themselves.

00:05:02.033 --> 00:05:03.020 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Exactly.

00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:04.270 align:middle line:90%
And Thomas Wolfe.

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:05.070 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yes.

00:05:05.070 --> 00:05:08.470 align:middle line:84%
The problem with the English
public school system,

00:05:08.470 --> 00:05:10.950 align:middle line:84%
as we call it
there, is that it's

00:05:10.950 --> 00:05:15.380 align:middle line:84%
a system that brutalizes
you mentally, first

00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:16.630 align:middle line:90%
physically, and then mentally.

00:05:16.630 --> 00:05:19.230 align:middle line:84%
And the idea behind
it was that it

00:05:19.230 --> 00:05:21.780 align:middle line:84%
was going to create
hundreds of thousands

00:05:21.780 --> 00:05:24.450 align:middle line:84%
of young boys, who were
young men, who would go

00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:26.000 align:middle line:90%
out and administer the empire.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.770 align:middle line:84%
And if you go back 100
years, go back 200 years,

00:05:29.770 --> 00:05:33.770 align:middle line:84%
what England was up to then
was conquering the planet.

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:35.660 align:middle line:84%
An awful lot of
manpower was needed

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:39.000 align:middle line:84%
to have these guys at
18, 21, et cetera, going

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.490 align:middle line:84%
to administer huge
areas of the Sudan

00:05:41.490 --> 00:05:44.369 align:middle line:84%
with an absolute sort of
firm belief in the empire--

00:05:44.369 --> 00:05:45.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Certainty, yes.

00:05:45.410 --> 00:05:46.150 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: --in themselves.

00:05:46.150 --> 00:05:48.370 align:middle line:84%
And most of them died of
malaria, and most of them

00:05:48.370 --> 00:05:50.950 align:middle line:84%
were killed in native
skirmishes or whatever,

00:05:50.950 --> 00:05:53.580 align:middle line:84%
and they had to sort of
just go into these things.

00:05:53.580 --> 00:05:56.030 align:middle line:84%
It's the same ethos that
took us over the top

00:05:56.030 --> 00:05:57.370 align:middle line:90%
in the World War II trenches.

00:05:57.370 --> 00:06:01.770 align:middle line:84%
There's a good side to
it-- the courage, the grit.

00:06:01.770 --> 00:06:03.755 align:middle line:84%
When we were in World
War II, for example,

00:06:03.755 --> 00:06:06.046 align:middle line:84%
we wouldn't have gotten
through the blitz without that.

00:06:06.046 --> 00:06:10.120 align:middle line:84%
But in terms of a way to go
through the modern world,

00:06:10.120 --> 00:06:11.440 align:middle line:90%
it's redundant, really.

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:15.445 align:middle line:84%
And so the problem was they told
us when we were little boys,

00:06:15.445 --> 00:06:17.320 align:middle line:84%
we're going to break
you down, and then we're

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:18.486 align:middle line:90%
going to build you up again.

00:06:18.486 --> 00:06:20.610 align:middle line:84%
And as we were
talking off camera,

00:06:20.610 --> 00:06:23.090 align:middle line:84%
the problem with it
when you're a child

00:06:23.090 --> 00:06:25.690 align:middle line:84%
is that you believe
what adults tell you.

00:06:25.690 --> 00:06:30.740 align:middle line:84%
And so the reality for
me-- and for anyone

00:06:30.740 --> 00:06:33.360 align:middle line:84%
who went through the
system-- was what you first

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:37.110 align:middle line:84%
contended with before the
physical stuff happened here

00:06:37.110 --> 00:06:42.210 align:middle line:84%
was this crushing, overwhelming
weight of adult sarcasm

00:06:42.210 --> 00:06:45.790 align:middle line:84%
and hostility that you couldn't
understand what you'd done.

00:06:45.790 --> 00:06:46.830 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And brutality.

00:06:46.830 --> 00:06:49.930 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Absolutely--
to engender.

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:51.800 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course,
they beat you as well.

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:54.330 align:middle line:84%
And then around about the
time you got to about 14,

00:06:54.330 --> 00:06:56.580 align:middle line:84%
and you started getting big,
they stopped beating you,

00:06:56.580 --> 00:06:58.040 align:middle line:84%
and they start giving
you privileges.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:06:59.498 align:middle line:84%
Right about the
time when you might

00:06:59.498 --> 00:07:02.420 align:middle line:84%
start fighting
back properly, then

00:07:02.420 --> 00:07:05.000 align:middle line:84%
you get the
privileges and so on.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.040 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It's so
painful to even hear,

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:09.210 align:middle line:84%
and I know other British
public school boys.

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:09.660 align:middle line:90%
It's very painful.

00:07:09.660 --> 00:07:12.035 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: The worst of it--
and it's even more corrupt,

00:07:12.035 --> 00:07:16.060 align:middle line:84%
really, in a way-- because
among the privileges

00:07:16.060 --> 00:07:18.700 align:middle line:84%
is the ability to then
discipline and brutalize

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:20.070 align:middle line:90%
younger boys.

00:07:20.070 --> 00:07:22.630 align:middle line:84%
So to visit upon
the younger boys

00:07:22.630 --> 00:07:24.830 align:middle line:90%
what's been visited upon you.

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:28.650 align:middle line:84%
And I remember being faced
with that choice when

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:31.750 align:middle line:84%
I was about 14, 15 and
realizing that this

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:35.434 align:middle line:84%
was one of those absolute
parts, forks in life--

00:07:35.434 --> 00:07:36.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: A defining moment.

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:38.750 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Yes,
that I could either

00:07:38.750 --> 00:07:42.200 align:middle line:84%
be that problem that
I had been surviving,

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:43.540 align:middle line:90%
or I could choose not to be.

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:45.831 align:middle line:84%
But if I chose not to be, I
would get no brownie points

00:07:45.831 --> 00:07:47.320 align:middle line:90%
from the institution.

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:49.419 align:middle line:84%
And I couldn't find
it in me to do it.

00:07:49.419 --> 00:07:50.710 align:middle line:90%
I did not want to be a prefect.

00:07:50.710 --> 00:07:53.410 align:middle line:84%
I did not want any jurisdiction
over the younger boys,

00:07:53.410 --> 00:07:57.980 align:middle line:84%
and I did not want to have
any part in their brutalizing.

00:07:57.980 --> 00:08:01.720 align:middle line:84%
And there were a lot of
people like me, obviously.

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:03.970 align:middle line:84%
And thank god those
of us who made

00:08:03.970 --> 00:08:06.540 align:middle line:84%
that choice made that choice,
because I think if you make

00:08:06.540 --> 00:08:08.873 align:middle line:84%
the other choice, you then
have to spend the next 30, 40

00:08:08.873 --> 00:08:10.970 align:middle line:84%
years unlearning that
particular thing,

00:08:10.970 --> 00:08:12.480 align:middle line:90%
and you're almost hamstrung.

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:13.310 align:middle line:84%
It's almost like having
a leg chopped off.

00:08:13.310 --> 00:08:14.893 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, it's
so desensitizing.

00:08:14.893 --> 00:08:16.750 align:middle line:84%
Then you have to
try to re-salvage

00:08:16.750 --> 00:08:18.810 align:middle line:84%
those parts of the soul,
so to speak, once again.

00:08:18.810 --> 00:08:19.130 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Exactly.

00:08:19.130 --> 00:08:21.300 align:middle line:84%
And if you then want to decent
family life or something

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:22.240 align:middle line:84%
like that, then it's
going to be tough.

00:08:22.240 --> 00:08:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And this all
happened in the city of London.

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:26.830 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: This happened in
the financial district, yeah.

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:30.230 align:middle line:84%
The school I was at was a very
old school, one of those 500

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:33.190 align:middle line:84%
or 600-year-old schools
that had been started

00:08:33.190 --> 00:08:36.659 align:middle line:84%
to produce boys to enter
the financial industry, even

00:08:36.659 --> 00:08:39.780 align:middle line:84%
in the 15th century, by the
aldermen of the city of London.

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:42.659 align:middle line:84%
City of London, if you're
an American viewer,

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:45.250 align:middle line:84%
what we call the city,
you guys call Wall Street.

00:08:45.250 --> 00:08:46.830 align:middle line:84%
And it actually
means the same thing.

00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:48.496 align:middle line:84%
Wall Street is Wall
Street, because it's

00:08:48.496 --> 00:08:51.800 align:middle line:84%
withinside the old
walled compound

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:56.260 align:middle line:84%
that the first Dutch
settlers put there

00:08:56.260 --> 00:08:58.760 align:middle line:84%
as a fortress, Battery
Park to the wall.

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:03.060 align:middle line:84%
And it's the square mile
of the old Roman fortress

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:05.790 align:middle line:84%
that became the medieval
financial district

00:09:05.790 --> 00:09:09.570 align:middle line:84%
that the Romans first put there
on top of the Celtic settlement

00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:13.420 align:middle line:84%
to make a bridgehead,
their fortress 2,000 years

00:09:13.420 --> 00:09:14.590 align:middle line:90%
before that in the UK.

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:16.830 align:middle line:84%
So the same process
of colonization--

00:09:16.830 --> 00:09:19.126 align:middle line:84%
they were colonizing
from southern Europe

00:09:19.126 --> 00:09:20.500 align:middle line:84%
up into northern
Europe, and then

00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:22.525 align:middle line:84%
the northern Europeans
colonized over to North America,

00:09:22.525 --> 00:09:25.150 align:middle line:84%
and you had all the Indians, all
the Celts, all the [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:25.150 --> 00:09:26.860 align:middle line:84%
looking at them from
the forest going,

00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:28.450 align:middle line:90%
hm, this looks like trouble.

00:09:28.450 --> 00:09:30.800 align:middle line:90%
And indeed, it was.

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:31.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:35.500 align:middle line:84%
So there you are right
in the belly of at all,

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:39.020 align:middle line:84%
receiving what is considered
to be the world's most

00:09:39.020 --> 00:09:42.340 align:middle line:90%
privileged education.

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:46.710 align:middle line:84%
And we've already spoken to the
challenges of that, and that

00:09:46.710 --> 00:09:49.900 align:middle line:84%
the redundancy of it
really in today's time.

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:54.770 align:middle line:84%
And alongside this, you
also had an affinity

00:09:54.770 --> 00:09:59.460 align:middle line:90%
for the equine world.

00:09:59.460 --> 00:10:02.600 align:middle line:84%
And you are a professional
horse trainer.

00:10:02.600 --> 00:10:03.930 align:middle line:90%
You're a horseman.

00:10:03.930 --> 00:10:05.990 align:middle line:84%
Talk a little bit about
how horses entered

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:08.420 align:middle line:84%
into the picture, because
this will figure large

00:10:08.420 --> 00:10:09.320 align:middle line:90%
into this story.

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:13.770 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Well, my parents
are as open as can be.

00:10:13.770 --> 00:10:16.810 align:middle line:84%
Middle of London, school in
the middle of London-- horses

00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:18.270 align:middle line:90%
were always my thing.

00:10:18.270 --> 00:10:21.420 align:middle line:84%
But these things often skip
generations in families.

00:10:21.420 --> 00:10:24.941 align:middle line:84%
I come from a long line
of light cavalry officers,

00:10:24.941 --> 00:10:26.190 align:middle line:90%
particularly in South African.

00:10:26.190 --> 00:10:27.190 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Light cavalry.

00:10:27.190 --> 00:10:30.650 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Light cavalry,
irregular cavalry,

00:10:30.650 --> 00:10:33.040 align:middle line:84%
meaning the sort of special
forces type cavalry who

00:10:33.040 --> 00:10:35.890 align:middle line:84%
would be skirmishes
on the-- there

00:10:35.890 --> 00:10:38.140 align:middle line:84%
are many of my family had
their own regiments for this

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:39.190 align:middle line:90%
in South Africa.

00:10:39.190 --> 00:10:41.980 align:middle line:84%
During the Bull War, in fact,
four of my great-great-uncles

00:10:41.980 --> 00:10:43.940 align:middle line:84%
had their own regiments
of light cavalry

00:10:43.940 --> 00:10:45.590 align:middle line:90%
on different sides of the wall.

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:47.120 align:middle line:90%
They fought on different sides.

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:48.240 align:middle line:90%
It runs in the blood.

00:10:48.240 --> 00:10:52.540 align:middle line:84%
And I was fortunate in that
I had an aunt, also South

00:10:52.540 --> 00:10:54.880 align:middle line:84%
African, who'd married into
the British fox hunting

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:59.219 align:middle line:84%
culture in Leicestershire,
which is the seat of that.

00:10:59.219 --> 00:11:01.010 align:middle line:84%
There's a connection
between Leicestershire

00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:02.410 align:middle line:84%
and fox hunting and
the founding fathers,

00:11:02.410 --> 00:11:03.870 align:middle line:90%
which you might want to go into.

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:04.440 align:middle line:90%
It's quite interesting.

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:04.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, yes.

00:11:04.600 --> 00:11:04.930 align:middle line:90%
Just go ahead.

00:11:04.930 --> 00:11:05.445 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Do you
want to digress?

00:11:05.445 --> 00:11:07.111 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, I
don't mind digressing.

00:11:07.111 --> 00:11:09.010 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: The
sport of fox hunting

00:11:09.010 --> 00:11:11.890 align:middle line:84%
began in England
in the 18th century

00:11:11.890 --> 00:11:13.830 align:middle line:84%
with the invention of
the thoroughbred horse

00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:17.460 align:middle line:84%
and the addiction
to speed and hunting

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:20.640 align:middle line:84%
small game fast across
country jumping big fences.

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:21.810 align:middle line:90%
Incredibly dangerous.

00:11:21.810 --> 00:11:24.870 align:middle line:84%
The Duke of Wellington
called it the image of war

00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:28.130 align:middle line:84%
without its guilt, and
only 25% of it's dangerous.

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:31.242 align:middle line:84%
So 25% of the danger of a
pitched battle is quite a lot,

00:11:31.242 --> 00:11:32.700 align:middle line:84%
and certainly
growing up with this,

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:34.780 align:middle line:84%
I saw people killed
and maimed next to me.

00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:38.040 align:middle line:84%
So the action and the adrenalin
side of it is incredibly--

00:11:38.040 --> 00:11:39.910 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: You take risks.

00:11:39.910 --> 00:11:42.140 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: But more
than say, snowboarding.

00:11:42.140 --> 00:11:45.590 align:middle line:84%
And anyway, around
that time, that

00:11:45.590 --> 00:11:49.800 align:middle line:84%
was when the English gentlemen
who were going over to Virginia

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:53.520 align:middle line:84%
and founding those big estates
like Lord Fairfax and so on,

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:57.730 align:middle line:84%
and teaming up with
better families of that

00:11:57.730 --> 00:12:00.570 align:middle line:84%
like the Washingtons,
et cetera-- they all

00:12:00.570 --> 00:12:02.160 align:middle line:84%
had their own
packs of foxhounds,

00:12:02.160 --> 00:12:05.400 align:middle line:84%
because it was what Jefferson,
Fairfax, George Washington had

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:06.600 align:middle line:90%
his own English foxhound.

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:09.190 align:middle line:84%
So right when this
culture was coming

00:12:09.190 --> 00:12:10.810 align:middle line:84%
to fruition in that
part of England

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:13.510 align:middle line:84%
where I was growing up,
in the mid-18th century,

00:12:13.510 --> 00:12:16.122 align:middle line:84%
it was also having a
parallel beginning here.

00:12:16.122 --> 00:12:17.580 align:middle line:84%
And it was almost
like freemasonry.

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:20.370 align:middle line:84%
It's sort of one of
these codes of gentlemen.

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:21.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It is.

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:22.090 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Things
that people did,

00:12:22.090 --> 00:12:23.620 align:middle line:90%
and it was a test of encourage.

00:12:23.620 --> 00:12:25.290 align:middle line:84%
And people wanted to
know who you hunted with,

00:12:25.290 --> 00:12:27.220 align:middle line:84%
because if you hunted
here, it was fashionable,

00:12:27.220 --> 00:12:28.410 align:middle line:90%
because it was more dangerous.

00:12:28.410 --> 00:12:30.326 align:middle line:84%
If you hunted there, it
wasn't as fashionable.

00:12:30.326 --> 00:12:32.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, I have
to say I had the-- well,

00:12:32.350 --> 00:12:34.580 align:middle line:84%
I was in a unique
situation one time, invited

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:38.370 align:middle line:84%
to a dinner party in Virginia,
an estate near Monticello,

00:12:38.370 --> 00:12:39.950 align:middle line:90%
near Jefferson's estate.

00:12:39.950 --> 00:12:42.500 align:middle line:84%
And I wasn't aware
until I arrived--

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:45.240 align:middle line:84%
I think I must have been
brought in as the entertainment

00:12:45.240 --> 00:12:46.040 align:middle line:90%
for the group.

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:46.870 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: You
came out of a cake.

00:12:46.870 --> 00:12:48.570 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah,
something like that.

00:12:48.570 --> 00:12:49.370 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:12:49.370 --> 00:12:53.540 align:middle line:84%
I was actually an invited guest,
but multinationals corporation

00:12:53.540 --> 00:12:56.560 align:middle line:84%
heads-- I won't name some
of the corporations-- hotels

00:12:56.560 --> 00:12:59.280 align:middle line:84%
and so forth-- were at
the dinner party, which

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:01.557 align:middle line:84%
was made vegetarian in
my honor, because I had

00:13:01.557 --> 00:13:03.140 align:middle line:84%
a vegetarian cooking
show at the time,

00:13:03.140 --> 00:13:05.600 align:middle line:84%
and the host just
happened to like me.

00:13:05.600 --> 00:13:08.200 align:middle line:84%
But I realized after
a minute or two,

00:13:08.200 --> 00:13:10.850 align:middle line:84%
this was all about
fox hunting season.

00:13:10.850 --> 00:13:11.650 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yes.

00:13:11.650 --> 00:13:13.190 align:middle line:90%
Virginia is the capitol here.

00:13:13.190 --> 00:13:16.250 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And I realized this
was how these people connected

00:13:16.250 --> 00:13:17.050 align:middle line:90%
and gathered--

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:17.490 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: It's an
international world.

00:13:17.490 --> 00:13:19.991 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --same time each year,
and it was a global affair.

00:13:19.991 --> 00:13:22.448 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: The first job I
ever did when I came to America

00:13:22.448 --> 00:13:24.800 align:middle line:84%
was training horses in the
hunt field in Virginia.

00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:25.990 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:13:25.990 --> 00:13:26.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:26.790 --> 00:13:29.232 align:middle line:84%
So now you had this
passion for horses,

00:13:29.232 --> 00:13:30.690 align:middle line:84%
and that's how you
began it, right?

00:13:30.690 --> 00:13:31.800 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: I did, yes.

00:13:31.800 --> 00:13:34.172 align:middle line:84%
And my parents
didn't have money.

00:13:34.172 --> 00:13:35.630 align:middle line:84%
You can go to these
private schools

00:13:35.630 --> 00:13:37.713 align:middle line:84%
and still not have money
if you have scholarships.

00:13:37.713 --> 00:13:39.330 align:middle line:84%
So I had a scholarship
as a choir boy.

00:13:39.330 --> 00:13:41.164 align:middle line:84%
I was a chorister at
the Temple Church.

00:13:41.164 --> 00:13:42.830 align:middle line:84%
If you're a conspiracy
theorist, and you

00:13:42.830 --> 00:13:47.980 align:middle line:84%
want to talk about the
Templars, and thereafter, I

00:13:47.980 --> 00:13:50.570 align:middle line:84%
was a chorister at
the Temple Church.

00:13:50.570 --> 00:13:53.532 align:middle line:84%
So there's the whole
other thing we could--

00:13:53.532 --> 00:13:54.990 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We won't
talk about that.

00:13:54.990 --> 00:13:56.840 align:middle line:90%
Maybe in another show.

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:58.570 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to
digress too far, but I

00:13:58.570 --> 00:13:59.840 align:middle line:84%
would love to do that
show with you as well.

00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:01.470 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: I was brought up
on the fringes of Dan Brown's

00:14:01.470 --> 00:14:01.810 align:middle line:90%
mind.

00:14:01.810 --> 00:14:02.830 align:middle line:90%
Put it that way.

00:14:02.830 --> 00:14:08.080 align:middle line:84%
And anyway, however, because
we had this family connection

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:13.110 align:middle line:84%
with horses, and then I started
a junk store at a flea market

00:14:13.110 --> 00:14:15.780 align:middle line:84%
when I was 12 to raise
money to buy a horse

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:20.550 align:middle line:84%
and would clear up people's
garages from junk and flog it,

00:14:20.550 --> 00:14:22.560 align:middle line:84%
and eventually
made enough money.

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:25.820 align:middle line:84%
And then under the
tutelage of old Virginia,

00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:30.120 align:middle line:84%
old Leicestershire horse
guys, got a racehorse

00:14:30.120 --> 00:14:32.014 align:middle line:90%
off the track that was retired.

00:14:32.014 --> 00:14:33.430 align:middle line:84%
That's a way to
get a cheap horse.

00:14:33.430 --> 00:14:35.388 align:middle line:84%
And then retrained him
as a fox hunter and then

00:14:35.388 --> 00:14:38.250 align:middle line:84%
as a sport horse, as an event,
as a show jumper, et cetera,

00:14:38.250 --> 00:14:40.520 align:middle line:90%
until I knew that job very well.

00:14:40.520 --> 00:14:42.655 align:middle line:84%
And that's how you
become a professional is

00:14:42.655 --> 00:14:44.780 align:middle line:84%
that frequently, if you
don't really have the money

00:14:44.780 --> 00:14:47.510 align:middle line:84%
to enter at the top level, you
sort of have to enter where you

00:14:47.510 --> 00:14:51.490 align:middle line:84%
can, and then it's this
sort of professionals

00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:55.170 align:middle line:84%
to the wealthy people, who then
give you your apprenticeship.

00:14:55.170 --> 00:14:56.735 align:middle line:84%
And so I had that
apprenticeship.

00:14:56.735 --> 00:14:58.360 align:middle line:84%
And that's been
something that's lasted

00:14:58.360 --> 00:14:59.180 align:middle line:90%
through the rest of my life.

00:14:59.180 --> 00:15:01.513 align:middle line:84%
It's one the best things that
could have happened to me.

00:15:01.513 --> 00:15:02.520 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:15:02.520 --> 00:15:03.430 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: That's a
skill that will take you.

00:15:03.430 --> 00:15:04.080 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You
would've never guessed

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:05.850 align:middle line:84%
how profound those
implications would

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:08.630 align:middle line:84%
be many, many years down the
road once you had your child.

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:08.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:08.950 --> 00:15:11.000 align:middle line:84%
So now we hear this
background, and most people

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.770 align:middle line:84%
are thinking, well, what a
plummy life that's been so far,

00:15:13.770 --> 00:15:15.150 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:15:15.150 --> 00:15:18.510 align:middle line:84%
So now you marry your
beautiful wife, Kristin.

00:15:18.510 --> 00:15:20.980 align:middle line:84%
You have a child, and
the child is what?

00:15:20.980 --> 00:15:23.110 align:middle line:84%
Three or four years old
when you get the diagnosis?

00:15:23.110 --> 00:15:24.590 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Two and 1/2, yeah.

00:15:24.590 --> 00:15:25.506 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Two and 1/2.

00:15:25.506 --> 00:15:27.750 align:middle line:84%
And so he's screaming
uncontrollably

00:15:27.750 --> 00:15:28.860 align:middle line:90%
four hours at a time.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:29.206 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yeah.

00:15:29.206 --> 00:15:29.900 align:middle line:90%
Oh, yeah.

00:15:29.900 --> 00:15:31.840 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And now your life is
like going to hell in one way.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:32.798 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Completely.

00:15:32.798 --> 00:15:34.850 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But you love
this beautiful little boy,

00:15:34.850 --> 00:15:38.430 align:middle line:84%
and you have nothing
really in your background

00:15:38.430 --> 00:15:40.412 align:middle line:84%
is going to prepare
you to deal with this.

00:15:40.412 --> 00:15:42.370 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Not as far
as I knew at that point.

00:15:42.370 --> 00:15:43.340 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So let's
talk about it.

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:45.215 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Well, one
of the things that I am

00:15:45.215 --> 00:15:47.740 align:middle line:84%
is I'm a journalist, so
that's what I became.

00:15:47.740 --> 00:15:48.720 align:middle line:90%
Yes, I do horses.

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:49.820 align:middle line:84%
And yes, I've done
them professionally.

00:15:49.820 --> 00:15:51.270 align:middle line:90%
I still do them professionally.

00:15:51.270 --> 00:15:53.700 align:middle line:84%
I'm also a journalist,
and I've written

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:55.360 align:middle line:84%
for all the British
press, and I'm

00:15:55.360 --> 00:15:57.920 align:middle line:90%
an author and so on and so on.

00:15:57.920 --> 00:16:02.190 align:middle line:84%
And so I'm a trained
observer, and one thing

00:16:02.190 --> 00:16:04.156 align:middle line:84%
I could do, because
my son was nonverbal--

00:16:04.156 --> 00:16:05.530 align:middle line:84%
couldn't tell me
what he wanted--

00:16:05.530 --> 00:16:08.220 align:middle line:84%
but I could observe what he
did physically with his body

00:16:08.220 --> 00:16:09.390 align:middle line:90%
and follow that.

00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:11.870 align:middle line:84%
So what he wanted
to be was outside,

00:16:11.870 --> 00:16:13.520 align:middle line:90%
and he tantrumed less outside.

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:17.160 align:middle line:84%
And there will be quite
a lot of viewers who are

00:16:17.160 --> 00:16:18.710 align:middle line:90%
dealing with autism right now.

00:16:18.710 --> 00:16:21.050 align:middle line:84%
For those viewers who are
dealing with autism right now,

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:23.280 align:middle line:84%
I know what you're
going through.

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:24.280 align:middle line:90%
I'll look at the camera.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:25.655 align:middle line:84%
I know what you're
going through.

00:16:25.655 --> 00:16:26.500 align:middle line:90%
I do.

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:29.472 align:middle line:84%
Those incessant,
neurologically-based tantrums--

00:16:29.472 --> 00:16:31.930 align:middle line:84%
there's nothing you can do,
except try to prevent the child

00:16:31.930 --> 00:16:32.980 align:middle line:90%
from self-harming.

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:35.770 align:middle line:84%
But out there in nature-- we
live in the countryside outside

00:16:35.770 --> 00:16:38.010 align:middle line:90%
of Austin, Texas in the woods.

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:38.960 align:middle line:90%
He wasn't tantruming.

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:40.980 align:middle line:84%
This was interesting,
so that's where we were.

00:16:40.980 --> 00:16:44.120 align:middle line:84%
And then one day he
saw my neighbor's mare

00:16:44.120 --> 00:16:44.920 align:middle line:90%
through the fence.

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:49.310 align:middle line:84%
Now I had given up horses,
because I thought my son was

00:16:49.310 --> 00:16:50.460 align:middle line:90%
not safe around horses.

00:16:50.460 --> 00:16:53.040 align:middle line:84%
So for me, I gave
up the thing that

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:55.540 align:middle line:84%
gave me the most joy
in life, and so you

00:16:55.540 --> 00:16:59.120 align:middle line:84%
can imagine what a downward
spiral of depression I was in.

00:16:59.120 --> 00:17:03.390 align:middle line:84%
I was heading down
a bottle quite fast.

00:17:03.390 --> 00:17:06.099 align:middle line:84%
But he spotted this
horse, and instead

00:17:06.099 --> 00:17:08.967 align:middle line:84%
of going right along the
trail as normal, went left,

00:17:08.967 --> 00:17:11.300 align:middle line:84%
and before I could grab him,
he'd gone through the fence

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:13.810 align:middle line:84%
and was on his back
under her hooves.

00:17:13.810 --> 00:17:16.849 align:middle line:84%
And I thought he was
going to get trampled.

00:17:16.849 --> 00:17:21.710 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to win most rubbish
dad of the century here.

00:17:21.710 --> 00:17:23.190 align:middle line:90%
I'm terrified.

00:17:23.190 --> 00:17:24.750 align:middle line:84%
I'm crawling up to
try and grab him

00:17:24.750 --> 00:17:27.740 align:middle line:84%
to pull him back under the
wire, but instead something

00:17:27.740 --> 00:17:29.320 align:middle line:90%
rather amazing happened.

00:17:29.320 --> 00:17:32.460 align:middle line:84%
Betsy, the name of this
horse, bent her head to him

00:17:32.460 --> 00:17:36.530 align:middle line:84%
and began to lick and chew
and half closed the eye.

00:17:36.530 --> 00:17:38.650 align:middle line:84%
And that behavior, if
you're a horse trainer,

00:17:38.650 --> 00:17:41.600 align:middle line:84%
it's a submission and
acceptance gesture,

00:17:41.600 --> 00:17:43.349 align:middle line:84%
very similar to a dog
showing it's belly.

00:17:43.349 --> 00:17:45.890 align:middle line:84%
And there are many, many ways
you can get a horse to do this,

00:17:45.890 --> 00:17:47.910 align:middle line:84%
because they have very
structured hierarchies

00:17:47.910 --> 00:17:50.350 align:middle line:84%
in their herds, so it's
not difficult to behave

00:17:50.350 --> 00:17:53.480 align:middle line:84%
like a dominant horse and get
a horse to do this to you.

00:17:53.480 --> 00:17:56.260 align:middle line:84%
In fact, you have to really
as part of the training.

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:57.400 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Here, you're
talking about a little child.

00:17:57.400 --> 00:17:59.775 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: I hadn't seen a
horse offer it spontaneously,

00:17:59.775 --> 00:18:02.700 align:middle line:84%
not to anyone, let alone a
babbling two and 1/2 year

00:18:02.700 --> 00:18:04.210 align:middle line:90%
old autistic kid on his back.

00:18:04.210 --> 00:18:09.000 align:middle line:84%
So clearly, there's some direct
line that I don't understand,

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:10.340 align:middle line:90%
but I can observe it.

00:18:10.340 --> 00:18:13.140 align:middle line:84%
So we would go back
and back to Betsy,

00:18:13.140 --> 00:18:15.310 align:middle line:84%
because he would just
run there in the morning.

00:18:15.310 --> 00:18:18.370 align:middle line:84%
And Betsy was an old quiet mare,
so I knew he wanted to get up.

00:18:18.370 --> 00:18:22.130 align:middle line:84%
He would show me by trying
to jump next to her.

00:18:22.130 --> 00:18:23.902 align:middle line:90%
So I would put him on her back.

00:18:23.902 --> 00:18:24.860 align:middle line:90%
She wasn't a big horse.

00:18:24.860 --> 00:18:27.000 align:middle line:84%
And I could hold him like
this while she grazed.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:27.800 align:middle line:90%
I knew the horse.

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:30.400 align:middle line:84%
I knew she was quiet
and older, and all

00:18:30.400 --> 00:18:33.667 align:middle line:84%
of his stimming, all
the repetitive motions,

00:18:33.667 --> 00:18:35.250 align:middle line:84%
chanting, flapping,
that sort of thing

00:18:35.250 --> 00:18:37.900 align:middle line:84%
that we associate with
autism-- we call it stimming,

00:18:37.900 --> 00:18:41.000 align:middle line:84%
self-stimulatory
activity-- stopped

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.450 align:middle line:84%
when he was up there like
that using her as a couch.

00:18:43.450 --> 00:18:46.060 align:middle line:84%
And it didn't occur to me
to ride with him, because I

00:18:46.060 --> 00:18:48.290 align:middle line:84%
come from the English
tradition where you don't learn

00:18:48.290 --> 00:18:50.220 align:middle line:84%
to ride in front of a parent,
because the English saddle

00:18:50.220 --> 00:18:51.020 align:middle line:90%
doesn't allow that.

00:18:51.020 --> 00:18:52.840 align:middle line:90%
You fall out the front.

00:18:52.840 --> 00:18:55.630 align:middle line:84%
So everyone starts on
the lunge line and so on.

00:18:55.630 --> 00:18:57.530 align:middle line:84%
But, of course, in
Texas, it's different.

00:18:57.530 --> 00:19:01.259 align:middle line:84%
So I spoke to my neighbor, and
he said, sure, give it a try.

00:19:01.259 --> 00:19:03.300 align:middle line:84%
And as luck would have
it, the saddle that he had

00:19:03.300 --> 00:19:06.776 align:middle line:84%
was for a big old Texas butt,
like a real oversized saddle.

00:19:06.776 --> 00:19:10.750 align:middle line:84%
So there's plenty of room for
me and him, and I got up there.

00:19:10.750 --> 00:19:13.424 align:middle line:84%
And on the first day that
I was riding with them,

00:19:13.424 --> 00:19:15.090 align:middle line:84%
I was sort of searching
for inspiration.

00:19:15.090 --> 00:19:18.930 align:middle line:84%
I always used to speak to
him sort of rhetorically,

00:19:18.930 --> 00:19:20.880 align:middle line:84%
a bit like having NPR
on in the background,

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:23.840 align:middle line:84%
assuming that he was taking in
more than he was understanding,

00:19:23.840 --> 00:19:26.100 align:middle line:84%
receptive versus
expressive language.

00:19:26.100 --> 00:19:28.470 align:middle line:84%
And so I would always be
like, well, there's the sky.

00:19:28.470 --> 00:19:28.690 align:middle line:90%
It's blue.

00:19:28.690 --> 00:19:29.330 align:middle line:90%
What is the sky?

00:19:29.330 --> 00:19:30.260 align:middle line:90%
What is the pump?

00:19:30.260 --> 00:19:30.870 align:middle line:90%
What is oxygen?

00:19:30.870 --> 00:19:31.640 align:middle line:90%
What is the atmosphere?

00:19:31.640 --> 00:19:32.820 align:middle line:90%
What's the pulmonary system?

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:34.653 align:middle line:84%
I'd talk like this,
because I thought, well,

00:19:34.653 --> 00:19:36.350 align:middle line:90%
one day, he probably will talk.

00:19:36.350 --> 00:19:37.972 align:middle line:90%
Anyway, we're up there.

00:19:37.972 --> 00:19:39.680 align:middle line:84%
I'm searching for
inspiration, so I said,

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:41.540 align:middle line:84%
should we go to the
woods or the pond?

00:19:41.540 --> 00:19:44.290 align:middle line:84%
And he had echolalia, which is
where they will repeat things

00:19:44.290 --> 00:19:45.694 align:middle line:84%
that they hear,
and they'll often

00:19:45.694 --> 00:19:47.360 align:middle line:84%
repeat the last three
words you've said,

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:49.200 align:middle line:84%
but they don't
really understand.

00:19:49.200 --> 00:19:52.114 align:middle line:84%
So he said, to the pond, which
is-- that's just echolalia.

00:19:52.114 --> 00:19:53.780 align:middle line:84%
Better than a kick
in the face, thought.

00:19:53.780 --> 00:19:53.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:53.950 --> 00:19:56.580 align:middle line:84%
So we go down to the pond,
and a big blue heron gets up

00:19:56.580 --> 00:19:57.380 align:middle line:90%
and flaps away.

00:19:57.380 --> 00:19:59.040 align:middle line:90%
And he said, heron.

00:19:59.040 --> 00:20:01.025 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't know
he knew that word.

00:20:01.025 --> 00:20:02.500 align:middle line:90%
I'm like, oh,

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:03.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: He's been listening.

00:20:03.840 --> 00:20:05.540 align:middle line:84%
He's been taking it
in on some level.

00:20:05.540 --> 00:20:07.740 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And then I
start giving him choices,

00:20:07.740 --> 00:20:09.656 align:middle line:84%
and he starts taking the
choices, directions--

00:20:09.656 --> 00:20:11.260 align:middle line:90%
left, right, fast or slow.

00:20:11.260 --> 00:20:14.300 align:middle line:84%
And I noticed very, very quickly
within that first session

00:20:14.300 --> 00:20:16.470 align:middle line:84%
that the more I go with
the canter, the lope,

00:20:16.470 --> 00:20:20.220 align:middle line:84%
as the Western people call
it, the more speech I get.

00:20:20.220 --> 00:20:21.262 align:middle line:90%
And I don't know why.

00:20:21.262 --> 00:20:22.470 align:middle line:90%
I don't know what's going on.

00:20:22.470 --> 00:20:24.410 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Some kind
of rhythmic something.

00:20:24.410 --> 00:20:25.210 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yes.

00:20:25.210 --> 00:20:26.975 align:middle line:84%
And subsequently, I
could now talk you

00:20:26.975 --> 00:20:29.100 align:middle line:84%
through the neurology of
exactly what was going on,

00:20:29.100 --> 00:20:30.980 align:middle line:90%
but at the time, had no idea.

00:20:30.980 --> 00:20:34.380 align:middle line:84%
So suddenly, I had
this thing that worked.

00:20:34.380 --> 00:20:36.240 align:middle line:84%
And it was ironic,
because that week

00:20:36.240 --> 00:20:38.510 align:middle line:84%
was the week that his speech
therapist gave up on him

00:20:38.510 --> 00:20:40.250 align:middle line:84%
and actually said,
sorry, I don't

00:20:40.250 --> 00:20:41.610 align:middle line:90%
think this kid will ever talk.

00:20:41.610 --> 00:20:44.940 align:middle line:84%
So we, for the next two
and 1/2, three years,

00:20:44.940 --> 00:20:47.410 align:middle line:84%
literally lived in the saddle
together three to four hours

00:20:47.410 --> 00:20:48.210 align:middle line:90%
a day.

00:20:48.210 --> 00:20:49.730 align:middle line:90%
And I took books up there.

00:20:49.730 --> 00:20:52.132 align:middle line:84%
I painted letters
on trees, and we'd

00:20:52.132 --> 00:20:54.590 align:middle line:84%
ride from one to the other,
putting them together into-- it

00:20:54.590 --> 00:20:55.615 align:middle line:90%
became "Lion King" characters.

00:20:55.615 --> 00:20:56.870 align:middle line:90%
He was into "The Lion King."

00:20:56.870 --> 00:20:58.828 align:middle line:84%
Intrinsic motivation--
there'd be a "Lion King"

00:20:58.828 --> 00:21:01.530 align:middle line:84%
toy waiting for him at the
end, and he learned to read.

00:21:01.530 --> 00:21:03.692 align:middle line:84%
And I did the same with
numbers, and he learned--

00:21:03.692 --> 00:21:05.400 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: As long as
he was on horseback.

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:06.858 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Yeah,
kinetic learning.

00:21:06.858 --> 00:21:10.160 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But-- and the horse
was cantering at the time.

00:21:10.160 --> 00:21:12.684 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Well, we got our
best results at the canter,

00:21:12.684 --> 00:21:13.850 align:middle line:90%
but you can't always canter.

00:21:13.850 --> 00:21:15.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: But that makes sense.

00:21:15.470 --> 00:21:19.320 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: But-- so when we
were working at the walk, say,

00:21:19.320 --> 00:21:23.030 align:middle line:84%
or the trot, I made sure that it
was the most rhythmic possible.

00:21:23.030 --> 00:21:24.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah,
because with autism,

00:21:24.820 --> 00:21:28.040 align:middle line:84%
this repetitious rhythmic
thing is going on anyway.

00:21:28.040 --> 00:21:30.614 align:middle line:84%
It's almost like
that laid a context.

00:21:30.614 --> 00:21:32.280 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: It's
actually for all of us.

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:34.350 align:middle line:84%
It's just that it's
more acute with them.

00:21:34.350 --> 00:21:35.640 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, interesting.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:37.680 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: So OK.

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:38.832 align:middle line:90%
Then Mongolia happens.

00:21:38.832 --> 00:21:41.290 align:middle line:84%
The reason Mongolia happened
is I have another side of my--

00:21:41.290 --> 00:21:43.706 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: OK, I have a question
before you go any further.

00:21:43.706 --> 00:21:45.230 align:middle line:84%
Before we get to
Mongolia, I want

00:21:45.230 --> 00:21:46.646 align:middle line:84%
to talk about
horses for a moment,

00:21:46.646 --> 00:21:50.220 align:middle line:84%
because you went to find
amazing horsemen in Mongolia

00:21:50.220 --> 00:21:52.720 align:middle line:84%
that the shamans
associated with horse,

00:21:52.720 --> 00:21:55.090 align:middle line:90%
and then later reindeers.

00:21:55.090 --> 00:21:56.270 align:middle line:90%
Let's back up a sec.

00:21:56.270 --> 00:21:58.390 align:middle line:90%
What is it about horses?

00:21:58.390 --> 00:22:01.160 align:middle line:84%
And two of my friends
are equine therapists.

00:22:01.160 --> 00:22:02.160 align:middle line:90%
What is it about horses?

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:03.230 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: The
horse-human connection?

00:22:03.230 --> 00:22:04.030 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:22:04.030 --> 00:22:05.320 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Well--

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:08.330 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Betsy would have known
to be gentle and submissive

00:22:08.330 --> 00:22:11.909 align:middle line:84%
to this little boy
under her hooves.

00:22:11.909 --> 00:22:13.450 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: I should
preface anything

00:22:13.450 --> 00:22:15.870 align:middle line:84%
I say by saying I'm
not a horse, and there

00:22:15.870 --> 00:22:18.790 align:middle line:84%
is a danger within
the equine therapy

00:22:18.790 --> 00:22:22.120 align:middle line:84%
world and the natural
horsemanship world and so on

00:22:22.120 --> 00:22:24.947 align:middle line:84%
to make assumptions that one
could speak for an animal.

00:22:24.947 --> 00:22:27.530 align:middle line:84%
And I'm very much of the belief
that that's actually hubristic

00:22:27.530 --> 00:22:28.450 align:middle line:90%
that one cannot.

00:22:28.450 --> 00:22:29.160 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I think you're right.

00:22:29.160 --> 00:22:29.960 align:middle line:90%
It is.

00:22:29.960 --> 00:22:32.700 align:middle line:84%
But as best you know as a
human, what do you observe?

00:22:32.700 --> 00:22:37.000 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: So Betsy is the
alpha mare of that herd.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:40.370 align:middle line:84%
In wild horse behavior,
the alpha mare

00:22:40.370 --> 00:22:42.566 align:middle line:84%
is a position that they
have more or less for life.

00:22:42.566 --> 00:22:43.440 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Alpha mare.

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:44.814 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Unlike
an alpha male.

00:22:44.814 --> 00:22:47.780 align:middle line:84%
An alpha male comes in, fights
his way out of a bachelor herd,

00:22:47.780 --> 00:22:51.690 align:middle line:84%
challenges the alpha
stallion, fights off

00:22:51.690 --> 00:22:54.260 align:middle line:84%
all comers for about two,
three years, then is exhausted

00:22:54.260 --> 00:22:56.640 align:middle line:84%
and is kicked out, and
another one comes in.

00:22:56.640 --> 00:22:59.950 align:middle line:84%
And his sole job really is
to provide sperm, the best

00:22:59.950 --> 00:23:01.270 align:middle line:90%
most vigorous sperm he can.

00:23:01.270 --> 00:23:03.590 align:middle line:84%
But he's usually not
the one who faces down

00:23:03.590 --> 00:23:05.145 align:middle line:84%
the predator, that
sort of thing,

00:23:05.145 --> 00:23:07.436 align:middle line:84%
makes the decisions about
when to change pastures or go

00:23:07.436 --> 00:23:08.540 align:middle line:90%
for water or that.

00:23:08.540 --> 00:23:09.840 align:middle line:90%
That's the alpha mare usually.

00:23:09.840 --> 00:23:10.881 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The alpha mare.

00:23:10.881 --> 00:23:12.590 align:middle line:90%
OK, interesting.

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:14.780 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And the alpha
mare holds that position

00:23:14.780 --> 00:23:16.670 align:middle line:84%
until she's about
ready to keel over,

00:23:16.670 --> 00:23:19.710 align:middle line:84%
and frequently, it's her
daughter or a close relation

00:23:19.710 --> 00:23:21.190 align:middle line:90%
who will take it over.

00:23:21.190 --> 00:23:28.050 align:middle line:84%
So within the alpha mare psyche,
to take care of a juvenile

00:23:28.050 --> 00:23:31.390 align:middle line:84%
is very much part
of their makeup.

00:23:31.390 --> 00:23:35.420 align:middle line:84%
And you see this happen
across species all the time.

00:23:35.420 --> 00:23:38.610 align:middle line:84%
If you've ever had to
bottle raise a lamb,

00:23:38.610 --> 00:23:39.930 align:middle line:90%
it accepts the bottle from you.

00:23:39.930 --> 00:23:42.344 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't just reject you
because you're a predator.

00:23:42.344 --> 00:23:44.010 align:middle line:84%
And then it will go
live with your dogs,

00:23:44.010 --> 00:23:45.956 align:middle line:84%
and the dogs will accept
it as another dog.

00:23:45.956 --> 00:23:47.330 align:middle line:84%
I've got a baby
goat in the house

00:23:47.330 --> 00:23:49.250 align:middle line:90%
right now that that's the story.

00:23:49.250 --> 00:23:54.200 align:middle line:84%
We see this kind of cross
species nurturing going on.

00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:58.650 align:middle line:84%
You'll see a dog will
suckle another species.

00:23:58.650 --> 00:24:00.010 align:middle line:90%
The list goes on.

00:24:00.010 --> 00:24:03.870 align:middle line:84%
So I think there was
something of that,

00:24:03.870 --> 00:24:06.260 align:middle line:84%
but there is an intangible
bond between the human

00:24:06.260 --> 00:24:08.040 align:middle line:84%
and the horse, because
the horse is not

00:24:08.040 --> 00:24:12.330 align:middle line:84%
the most effective and reliable
transport animal that we have.

00:24:12.330 --> 00:24:15.590 align:middle line:84%
Mules, donkeys, and camels
are much more reliable.

00:24:15.590 --> 00:24:18.680 align:middle line:84%
Elephants are, ironically,
easier to train than horses.

00:24:18.680 --> 00:24:21.255 align:middle line:84%
Horses are completely
dominated by their amygdala.

00:24:21.255 --> 00:24:23.630 align:middle line:84%
We're going to return to the
amygdala in a minute talking

00:24:23.630 --> 00:24:25.330 align:middle line:84%
about autism, which is
the part of your brain

00:24:25.330 --> 00:24:26.955 align:middle line:84%
that governs fight,
flight, and freeze.

00:24:26.955 --> 00:24:29.674 align:middle line:84%
And they solve their problems
by running away violently.

00:24:29.674 --> 00:24:30.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right, they spook.

00:24:30.840 --> 00:24:32.798 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And they
weigh what a truck weighs.

00:24:32.798 --> 00:24:34.700 align:middle line:84%
And you're working
with this thing.

00:24:34.700 --> 00:24:36.840 align:middle line:84%
Everyone who works
with horses gets hurt.

00:24:36.840 --> 00:24:39.270 align:middle line:90%
Why do we continue to do it?

00:24:39.270 --> 00:24:42.260 align:middle line:84%
Well, obviously,
in the old days,

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:44.250 align:middle line:84%
there was no thing
that you could

00:24:44.250 --> 00:24:46.295 align:middle line:84%
go to battle on that
was as effective--

00:24:46.295 --> 00:24:46.780 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Well, speed.

00:24:46.780 --> 00:24:47.990 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: --for
that very reason.

00:24:47.990 --> 00:24:50.240 align:middle line:84%
Well, there's many things
that are as fast as a horse.

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:52.210 align:middle line:84%
An elephant's as
fast as a horse.

00:24:52.210 --> 00:24:53.010 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Really?

00:24:53.010 --> 00:24:53.660 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yeah, yeah.

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:54.743 align:middle line:90%
I mean your average horse.

00:24:54.743 --> 00:24:57.480 align:middle line:84%
Not a racehorse, but an elephant
could do 30, 35 miles an hour

00:24:57.480 --> 00:24:59.800 align:middle line:90%
for sure, yeah.

00:24:59.800 --> 00:25:04.810 align:middle line:84%
Camels go fast, but
horses are maneuverable,

00:25:04.810 --> 00:25:06.840 align:middle line:84%
and horses have a certain
aggression in them

00:25:06.840 --> 00:25:09.050 align:middle line:90%
that you can tap into.

00:25:09.050 --> 00:25:11.230 align:middle line:84%
And then they can
become an extension

00:25:11.230 --> 00:25:12.900 align:middle line:90%
of the human on their back.

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:14.750 align:middle line:84%
And it's this quality
they have more

00:25:14.750 --> 00:25:16.375 align:middle line:84%
than any of the others
except, perhaps,

00:25:16.375 --> 00:25:19.450 align:middle line:84%
the elephant of draft
animals that carry us,

00:25:19.450 --> 00:25:21.150 align:middle line:90%
that makes a horse exceptional.

00:25:21.150 --> 00:25:25.140 align:middle line:84%
So a human being can project
his thoughts, his/her thoughts

00:25:25.140 --> 00:25:28.820 align:middle line:90%
and dreams through the horse.

00:25:28.820 --> 00:25:35.910 align:middle line:84%
So what horses represent
to us is dream and freedom.

00:25:35.910 --> 00:25:38.260 align:middle line:84%
And we become superhuman
the moment we're on a horse.

00:25:38.260 --> 00:25:40.730 align:middle line:84%
We're more beautiful, because
horses are so aesthetically

00:25:40.730 --> 00:25:42.480 align:middle line:84%
beautiful, so the
moment we sit on one,

00:25:42.480 --> 00:25:43.730 align:middle line:90%
we become part of that beauty.

00:25:43.730 --> 00:25:44.200 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It's true.

00:25:44.200 --> 00:25:45.201 align:middle line:90%
People feel transformed.

00:25:45.201 --> 00:25:46.825 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Well,
they are transformed.

00:25:46.825 --> 00:25:48.290 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
problems with this

00:25:48.290 --> 00:25:50.590 align:middle line:84%
is that it can lead to
an explosion and then

00:25:50.590 --> 00:25:52.075 align:middle line:90%
implosion of the human ego.

00:25:52.075 --> 00:25:54.930 align:middle line:84%
A lot of horse people are
not terribly nice people,

00:25:54.930 --> 00:25:57.921 align:middle line:84%
because you are bigger,
better, faster as long

00:25:57.921 --> 00:25:58.920 align:middle line:90%
as you're on that horse.

00:25:58.920 --> 00:25:59.860 align:middle line:84%
As soon as you
get off the horse,

00:25:59.860 --> 00:26:00.930 align:middle line:90%
you're like anybody else.

00:26:00.930 --> 00:26:02.200 align:middle line:84%
So if you live your
life on horseback--

00:26:02.200 --> 00:26:04.130 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, just take that
to the extreme in the polo

00:26:04.130 --> 00:26:04.630 align:middle line:90%
clubs.

00:26:04.630 --> 00:26:05.588 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Absolutely.

00:26:05.588 --> 00:26:08.810 align:middle line:84%
You can start to really
believe your own BS there.

00:26:08.810 --> 00:26:10.670 align:middle line:84%
Now the horse will
chuck you up from time

00:26:10.670 --> 00:26:12.830 align:middle line:84%
to time in front of people
and embarrass you, which

00:26:12.830 --> 00:26:14.080 align:middle line:90%
brings you back down to earth.

00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:17.302 align:middle line:84%
But nonetheless, that's
why the kings would always

00:26:17.302 --> 00:26:19.010 align:middle line:84%
say it was the only
honest counselor they

00:26:19.010 --> 00:26:19.885 align:middle line:90%
had was their horses.

00:26:19.885 --> 00:26:23.920 align:middle line:84%
The horse would dump you
in front of your populace.

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:27.870 align:middle line:84%
But even your faithful
do won't do that.

00:26:27.870 --> 00:26:30.510 align:middle line:84%
So horses do play this
role with humanity,

00:26:30.510 --> 00:26:32.350 align:middle line:84%
and I think that
in the 6,000 years

00:26:32.350 --> 00:26:35.190 align:middle line:84%
or so that we've
domesticated them,

00:26:35.190 --> 00:26:37.076 align:middle line:84%
there's been a human-horse
connection that's

00:26:37.076 --> 00:26:41.102 align:middle line:84%
caused a certain genetic melding
of certain types of people

00:26:41.102 --> 00:26:42.810 align:middle line:84%
with that animal like
there's dog people,

00:26:42.810 --> 00:26:44.726 align:middle line:84%
there's horse people,
there's elephant people,

00:26:44.726 --> 00:26:47.850 align:middle line:84%
there's camel people,
bird people, et cetera.

00:26:47.850 --> 00:26:53.030 align:middle line:84%
So Rowan comes from a
line of horse people.

00:26:53.030 --> 00:26:55.200 align:middle line:84%
It seems to be
there, and that seems

00:26:55.200 --> 00:26:58.140 align:middle line:84%
to be perhaps what's going
on with the Betsy connection.

00:26:58.140 --> 00:27:00.590 align:middle line:84%
But of course, there's an
intangible beyond that that one

00:27:00.590 --> 00:27:01.740 align:middle line:90%
can't put one's finger on.

00:27:01.740 --> 00:27:03.286 align:middle line:90%
It's a spiritual connection.

00:27:03.286 --> 00:27:04.660 align:middle line:84%
And the whole
point of the spirit

00:27:04.660 --> 00:27:06.845 align:middle line:84%
is one isn't supposed
to understand it.

00:27:06.845 --> 00:27:09.190 align:middle line:84%
I'm very comfortable
saying I don't know.

00:27:09.190 --> 00:27:12.910 align:middle line:84%
I don't understand, but
I'm very grateful that I'm

00:27:12.910 --> 00:27:15.400 align:middle line:84%
a recipient of that
spiritual generosity.

00:27:15.400 --> 00:27:16.200 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:27:16.200 --> 00:27:19.990 align:middle line:84%
So from there, we take
the spirit to Mongolia.

00:27:19.990 --> 00:27:21.540 align:middle line:90%
Your wife says, are you crazy?

00:27:21.540 --> 00:27:22.980 align:middle line:84%
What are you doing
to our family?

00:27:22.980 --> 00:27:24.021 align:middle line:90%
What are you doing to me?

00:27:24.021 --> 00:27:26.700 align:middle line:90%
What are you doing to our son?

00:27:26.700 --> 00:27:28.530 align:middle line:90%
But you all packed up, and--

00:27:28.530 --> 00:27:30.920 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Well, there was
a reason we went to Mongolia.

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:32.360 align:middle line:10%
It wasn't a random decision.

00:27:32.360 --> 00:27:34.500 align:middle line:10%
I have another professional
side of my life

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:35.920 align:middle line:10%
that we haven't discussed.

00:27:35.920 --> 00:27:39.000 align:middle line:84%
I'm a human rights
advocate in Africa.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:44.180 align:middle line:84%
My area is finding legal title
to ancestral land for hunting

00:27:44.180 --> 00:27:45.340 align:middle line:90%
and gathering tribes.

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:49.500 align:middle line:84%
So imagine in America 150 years
ago before Indian reservations,

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:52.460 align:middle line:84%
there were people out there
working on behalf of, say,

00:27:52.460 --> 00:27:54.590 align:middle line:84%
the Navajo tribe
or another tribe

00:27:54.590 --> 00:27:57.080 align:middle line:84%
to get them legal
title to this area,

00:27:57.080 --> 00:27:59.841 align:middle line:84%
fighting it through
in government,

00:27:59.841 --> 00:28:01.340 align:middle line:84%
and getting those
people onto there.

00:28:01.340 --> 00:28:04.160 align:middle line:84%
And that would be me, and
I've done that in Botswana

00:28:04.160 --> 00:28:06.860 align:middle line:84%
with hunting and gathering
called the Bushmen.

00:28:06.860 --> 00:28:09.240 align:middle line:84%
And it's because of my
family connections to them.

00:28:09.240 --> 00:28:11.960 align:middle line:84%
So the year that Rowan
was diagnosed with autism,

00:28:11.960 --> 00:28:13.597 align:middle line:84%
and the same year
that he met Betsy,

00:28:13.597 --> 00:28:15.180 align:middle line:84%
I had to bring a
delegation of Bushmen

00:28:15.180 --> 00:28:17.840 align:middle line:84%
to the United Nations and
the US State Department,

00:28:17.840 --> 00:28:20.030 align:middle line:84%
preparing to taking their
government to court.

00:28:20.030 --> 00:28:22.110 align:middle line:84%
And some of these guys
on that delegation

00:28:22.110 --> 00:28:24.630 align:middle line:84%
were trained healers and
shamans in their own culture.

00:28:24.630 --> 00:28:27.070 align:middle line:84%
They met Rowan as
part of the journey.

00:28:27.070 --> 00:28:29.520 align:middle line:84%
And they naturally said, oh,
we could do some work on him.

00:28:29.520 --> 00:28:31.055 align:middle line:90%
And I thought, well, why not?

00:28:31.055 --> 00:28:31.930 align:middle line:90%
Knock yourselves out.

00:28:31.930 --> 00:28:32.920 align:middle line:90%
It's just prayer.

00:28:32.920 --> 00:28:34.690 align:middle line:90%
Go for it.

00:28:34.690 --> 00:28:39.820 align:middle line:90%
And to my-- it was intriguing.

00:28:39.820 --> 00:28:45.540 align:middle line:84%
Rowan really lost a lot of
the most obsessive symptoms

00:28:45.540 --> 00:28:48.130 align:middle line:84%
of his autism in the five
days that he was with them.

00:28:48.130 --> 00:28:50.380 align:middle line:84%
Now he fell back
again when they left,

00:28:50.380 --> 00:28:53.340 align:middle line:84%
but I couldn't help but notice,
OK, radical and positive

00:28:53.340 --> 00:28:54.530 align:middle line:90%
reaction to the horse.

00:28:54.530 --> 00:28:56.930 align:middle line:84%
Radical and positive
reaction to these shamans.

00:28:56.930 --> 00:28:58.620 align:middle line:84%
And I'm familiar with
that world anyway,

00:28:58.620 --> 00:29:00.580 align:middle line:84%
because I saw my first
shamanic ceremony

00:29:00.580 --> 00:29:03.287 align:middle line:84%
on my grandfather's farm in
Zimbabwe when I was seven.

00:29:03.287 --> 00:29:04.870 align:middle line:84%
We talked about my
English upbringing.

00:29:04.870 --> 00:29:06.786 align:middle line:84%
We haven't talked about
my African upbringing.

00:29:06.786 --> 00:29:10.020 align:middle line:84%
I had a hybrid, slightly
schizophrenic upbringing.

00:29:10.020 --> 00:29:14.087 align:middle line:84%
So to me, all the
other things we

00:29:14.087 --> 00:29:16.295 align:middle line:84%
were trying-- the collation
therapy, the ABA therapy,

00:29:16.295 --> 00:29:19.156 align:middle line:84%
the behavioral therapy, the
speech therapy, the OT, all

00:29:19.156 --> 00:29:20.780 align:middle line:84%
that were not really
working very well.

00:29:20.780 --> 00:29:21.390 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, you
see in the film,

00:29:21.390 --> 00:29:23.655 align:middle line:84%
I mean just the
cocktails in the morning

00:29:23.655 --> 00:29:26.030 align:middle line:84%
that you were putting together
to get the right nutrients

00:29:26.030 --> 00:29:28.760 align:middle line:84%
and probiotics and vitamins
and everything else.

00:29:28.760 --> 00:29:29.860 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And we
weren't even giving drugs.

00:29:29.860 --> 00:29:31.230 align:middle line:84%
We were just trying to do all
these supplements and so on.

00:29:31.230 --> 00:29:33.290 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Everything
that you knew to do.

00:29:33.290 --> 00:29:34.430 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: We did.

00:29:34.430 --> 00:29:36.910 align:middle line:84%
But nothing happened as
radical as a reaction

00:29:36.910 --> 00:29:39.690 align:middle line:84%
as these two things, so it was
natural for me to say, well,

00:29:39.690 --> 00:29:42.440 align:middle line:84%
is there somewhere on the planet
that combines these two things?

00:29:42.440 --> 00:29:44.010 align:middle line:90%
And if so, should we go there?

00:29:44.010 --> 00:29:46.260 align:middle line:84%
It's not Africa, because
it's not a horse culture.

00:29:46.260 --> 00:29:48.930 align:middle line:84%
It's not here, because the
horse doesn't come from here.

00:29:48.930 --> 00:29:50.530 align:middle line:90%
Where does the horse come from?

00:29:50.530 --> 00:29:51.330 align:middle line:90%
Mongolia.

00:29:51.330 --> 00:29:52.130 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:29:52.130 --> 00:29:53.790 align:middle line:84%
Let's take a little
look at a clip.

00:29:53.790 --> 00:29:54.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:54.590 --> 00:29:55.521 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:29:55.521 --> 00:29:59.000 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:07.460 align:middle line:90%


00:30:07.460 --> 00:30:10.756 align:middle line:84%
-Our guide, Tulga, picked
us up at the airport

00:30:10.756 --> 00:30:13.980 align:middle line:84%
and took us into the
capital of Ulan Bator.

00:30:13.980 --> 00:30:16.280 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what I
was expecting exactly,

00:30:16.280 --> 00:30:20.380 align:middle line:84%
but this depressed, post-Soviet
city wasn't quite it.

00:30:20.380 --> 00:30:24.500 align:middle line:84%
I'd expected the open step,
nomads, horses, Genghis Khan

00:30:24.500 --> 00:30:27.290 align:middle line:84%
and all his warriors,
not an urban slum.

00:30:27.290 --> 00:30:31.505 align:middle line:90%


00:30:31.505 --> 00:30:33.755 align:middle line:84%
-I think it wasn't exactly
Rowan's vision of Mongolia.

00:30:33.755 --> 00:30:41.880 align:middle line:90%


00:30:41.880 --> 00:30:42.870 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:30:42.870 --> 00:30:43.670 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:30:43.670 --> 00:30:47.270 align:middle line:84%
So you arrived, essentially,
as you say, a Soviet slum.

00:30:47.270 --> 00:30:49.100 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Ulan Bator.

00:30:49.100 --> 00:30:51.040 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you go
from there, but let's

00:30:51.040 --> 00:30:54.500 align:middle line:84%
talk about the
quality of the people

00:30:54.500 --> 00:30:57.190 align:middle line:84%
you were meeting once you
got away from the city.

00:30:57.190 --> 00:31:02.360 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Even in the
city, actually, in Mongolia,

00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:05.130 align:middle line:84%
you're either in the middle
of a sort of post-Soviet slum,

00:31:05.130 --> 00:31:06.880 align:middle line:84%
or you're on the
step with nomads,

00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:08.629 align:middle line:90%
and there's no like transitions.

00:31:08.629 --> 00:31:09.920 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: There are no suburbs.

00:31:09.920 --> 00:31:10.605 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: No,
there's no suburbs,

00:31:10.605 --> 00:31:12.320 align:middle line:90%
and there's no farmland.

00:31:12.320 --> 00:31:15.590 align:middle line:84%
So the people in the
city really told us

00:31:15.590 --> 00:31:18.500 align:middle line:84%
we have the same quality as
the people in the countryside.

00:31:18.500 --> 00:31:23.460 align:middle line:84%
And the people in the
countryside are all Buddhists.

00:31:23.460 --> 00:31:24.970 align:middle line:84%
They're incredibly
accepting people.

00:31:24.970 --> 00:31:26.360 align:middle line:90%
They're incredibly open people.

00:31:26.360 --> 00:31:28.090 align:middle line:90%
They're incredibly warm people.

00:31:28.090 --> 00:31:30.990 align:middle line:84%
Even though life is
physically quite demanding,

00:31:30.990 --> 00:31:32.680 align:middle line:84%
the quality of
life is very high.

00:31:32.680 --> 00:31:34.490 align:middle line:90%
Everyone is self-determined.

00:31:34.490 --> 00:31:36.000 align:middle line:90%
They have gender equality.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:41.760 align:middle line:84%
They all have enough physical
resources for well-being.

00:31:41.760 --> 00:31:43.480 align:middle line:84%
They're living very,
very close to nature

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:47.800 align:middle line:84%
in a very fulfilling way--
horses, working with livestock,

00:31:47.800 --> 00:31:50.730 align:middle line:84%
working with ancestors, this
shamanic spiritual technology

00:31:50.730 --> 00:31:53.360 align:middle line:84%
that they're using all the
time alongside the Buddhism.

00:31:53.360 --> 00:31:58.560 align:middle line:84%
So this creates happy human
beings, who are very accepting.

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:01.237 align:middle line:84%
And it's interesting, because
they weren't always like that.

00:32:01.237 --> 00:32:03.070 align:middle line:84%
If you think about what
Mongolia represented

00:32:03.070 --> 00:32:04.029 align:middle line:90%
in the medieval times--

00:32:04.029 --> 00:32:04.986 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Genghis Khan.

00:32:04.986 --> 00:32:07.470 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Yeah, they would
explode every two generations

00:32:07.470 --> 00:32:10.690 align:middle line:84%
and kill everybody from the
Pacific to the Mediterranean,

00:32:10.690 --> 00:32:11.870 align:middle line:90%
and they go home again.

00:32:11.870 --> 00:32:13.710 align:middle line:84%
And what made them
stop, and what

00:32:13.710 --> 00:32:17.280 align:middle line:84%
made them stop was
in the 17th century,

00:32:17.280 --> 00:32:20.530 align:middle line:84%
some Tibetan monks walked
over the Altai Plateau,

00:32:20.530 --> 00:32:22.440 align:middle line:84%
and introduced this
idea called Buddhism.

00:32:22.440 --> 00:32:24.190 align:middle line:84%
And it was one of those
moments in history

00:32:24.190 --> 00:32:26.130 align:middle line:84%
a little bit like
the fall of apartheid

00:32:26.130 --> 00:32:28.320 align:middle line:84%
or the bringing down
of the Berlin Wall

00:32:28.320 --> 00:32:31.720 align:middle line:84%
or really the birth
of the United Nations

00:32:31.720 --> 00:32:34.220 align:middle line:84%
and the EU after World
War II and 10,000

00:32:34.220 --> 00:32:36.839 align:middle line:84%
years of tribal warfare in
Western Europe of people

00:32:36.839 --> 00:32:38.880 align:middle line:84%
sort of collectively
saying, yeah, you know what?

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:39.796 align:middle line:90%
Why are we doing this?

00:32:39.796 --> 00:32:43.080 align:middle line:90%
And choosing this better way.

00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:44.580 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But, still
that hardiness.

00:32:44.580 --> 00:32:46.630 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: They're hardy,
but they're not aggressive.

00:32:46.630 --> 00:32:47.671 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right, exactly.

00:32:47.671 --> 00:32:49.850 align:middle line:84%
That's a beautiful
combination of traits.

00:32:49.850 --> 00:32:51.420 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: But loving.

00:32:51.420 --> 00:32:52.510 align:middle line:90%
They're compassionate.

00:32:52.510 --> 00:32:54.010 align:middle line:84%
What defines Buddhism
is compassion.

00:32:54.010 --> 00:32:54.900 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:32:54.900 --> 00:32:57.150 align:middle line:84%
The other thing that
has always struck me

00:32:57.150 --> 00:33:00.820 align:middle line:84%
about their lifestyle in other
films and books I've read

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:03.450 align:middle line:84%
and so forth is that there
is this element that's

00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:06.840 align:middle line:84%
incorporated that there's
still time to create beauty

00:33:06.840 --> 00:33:09.850 align:middle line:84%
in their homes-- the textiles,
the colors, the carvings,

00:33:09.850 --> 00:33:10.760 align:middle line:90%
the paintings.

00:33:10.760 --> 00:33:11.070 align:middle line:90%
This is beautiful.

00:33:11.070 --> 00:33:11.830 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: This is
what you see actually

00:33:11.830 --> 00:33:13.270 align:middle line:90%
in all indigenous societies.

00:33:13.270 --> 00:33:17.590 align:middle line:84%
There's this idea that you need
to work as frenetically as we

00:33:17.590 --> 00:33:22.730 align:middle line:84%
do to have leisure to create
art, conversation, cuisine,

00:33:22.730 --> 00:33:23.720 align:middle line:90%
culture.

00:33:23.720 --> 00:33:25.180 align:middle line:90%
That's not true.

00:33:25.180 --> 00:33:29.950 align:middle line:84%
What you need is
competence economically.

00:33:29.950 --> 00:33:32.920 align:middle line:84%
So if you're economically
competent at sheep rearing,

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:35.400 align:middle line:84%
if you're economically competent
at hunting and gathering,

00:33:35.400 --> 00:33:37.400 align:middle line:84%
if you're economically
competent at Wall Street,

00:33:37.400 --> 00:33:39.760 align:middle line:84%
actually all roughly
amounts to the same thing

00:33:39.760 --> 00:33:43.710 align:middle line:84%
that you have a certain
leisure time, therefore,

00:33:43.710 --> 00:33:45.874 align:middle line:84%
to indulge in the
arts and the sciences.

00:33:45.874 --> 00:33:46.790 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And they do.

00:33:46.790 --> 00:33:48.370 align:middle line:84%
And it's represented
in every home.

00:33:48.370 --> 00:33:49.510 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Absolutely, they do.

00:33:49.510 --> 00:33:49.950 align:middle line:90%
No, absolutely.

00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:51.500 align:middle line:84%
The quality of life
is very high that way.

00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:53.291 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So you have
high quality of life.

00:33:53.291 --> 00:33:55.080 align:middle line:84%
You have peaceful
people who are hardy,

00:33:55.080 --> 00:33:56.590 align:middle line:84%
but who have also
carried through

00:33:56.590 --> 00:33:57.880 align:middle line:90%
their shamanic traditions.

00:33:57.880 --> 00:33:58.700 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yes.

00:33:58.700 --> 00:34:02.470 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so let's talk
about the initial contact.

00:34:02.470 --> 00:34:05.550 align:middle line:84%
When you're watching
the film-- hey,

00:34:05.550 --> 00:34:09.409 align:middle line:84%
let's just put a little
cut here in the film, where

00:34:09.409 --> 00:34:13.179 align:middle line:84%
I think it's Kristin is dealing
with the shaman, who saying,

00:34:13.179 --> 00:34:14.679 align:middle line:90%
OK, this is for the parents too.

00:34:14.679 --> 00:34:17.380 align:middle line:84%
And she's out of breath
jumping up and down,

00:34:17.380 --> 00:34:19.798 align:middle line:84%
and there's a little
flogging and such going on.

