00:34:55.710 --> 00:34:56.870 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yes, I can.

00:34:56.870 --> 00:34:58.911 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Are you trying
to get rid of the evil--

00:34:58.911 --> 00:35:02.280 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: No, I was as
freaked out and bemused by that

00:35:02.280 --> 00:35:04.760 align:middle line:84%
as you would be, because
I had so much experience

00:35:04.760 --> 00:35:07.390 align:middle line:84%
with shamanism in
Africa with the Bushmen,

00:35:07.390 --> 00:35:10.210 align:middle line:84%
where their method of doing
it is completely different.

00:35:10.210 --> 00:35:14.000 align:middle line:84%
And the Bushmen healer
suffers for you.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.100 align:middle line:84%
If you have a Bushmen
healer working on you,

00:35:16.100 --> 00:35:18.590 align:middle line:84%
he'll be pulling at you,
and you'll see him bleed.

00:35:18.590 --> 00:35:19.390 align:middle line:90%
He'll bleed.

00:35:19.390 --> 00:35:21.015 align:middle line:84%
He'll physically
start to bleed, things

00:35:21.015 --> 00:35:23.010 align:middle line:90%
like this on your behalf.

00:35:23.010 --> 00:35:24.140 align:middle line:90%
He takes on all the pain.

00:35:24.140 --> 00:35:25.765 align:middle line:84%
You feel this absolute
sort of blissful

00:35:25.765 --> 00:35:27.100 align:middle line:90%
buzzing through your body.

00:35:27.100 --> 00:35:28.884 align:middle line:90%
But the opposite in Mongolia.

00:35:28.884 --> 00:35:30.300 align:middle line:84%
The idea is that
it's a catharsis.

00:35:30.300 --> 00:35:31.936 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You all
took a beating.

00:35:31.936 --> 00:35:34.630 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: So we got whipped.

00:35:34.630 --> 00:35:37.660 align:middle line:84%
We got vodka and reindeer
spat in our faces.

00:35:37.660 --> 00:35:40.840 align:middle line:84%
Kristin had to wash
her lady parts out,

00:35:40.840 --> 00:35:44.219 align:middle line:84%
her childbearing
parts out with vodka.

00:35:44.219 --> 00:35:45.760 align:middle line:84%
On camera, there's
this hilarious bit

00:35:45.760 --> 00:35:48.830 align:middle line:84%
in the movie, where Michael,
who's making the documentary,

00:35:48.830 --> 00:35:51.315 align:middle line:84%
is trying to be true
to the documentary,

00:35:51.315 --> 00:35:52.720 align:middle line:84%
but he's desperately
embarrassed,

00:35:52.720 --> 00:35:55.410 align:middle line:84%
because Kristin's washing
out her vagina with vodka.

00:35:55.410 --> 00:35:58.190 align:middle line:84%
And she sort of turns
to him and says,

00:35:58.190 --> 00:36:00.400 align:middle line:84%
well, you'll Photoshop
out my cellulite, right?

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:03.390 align:middle line:84%
And it's sort of that
moment of wry humor

00:36:03.390 --> 00:36:05.650 align:middle line:90%
like we're all in this together.

00:36:05.650 --> 00:36:08.130 align:middle line:84%
And Rowan's reaction
initially was not good,

00:36:08.130 --> 00:36:09.130 align:middle line:90%
and I thought, oh, dear.

00:36:09.130 --> 00:36:12.920 align:middle line:84%
Have I made a terrible,
terrible, terrible mistake?

00:36:12.920 --> 00:36:15.380 align:middle line:84%
What happened was halfway
through that first ceremony

00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:17.230 align:middle line:84%
that was so difficult
and challenging,

00:36:17.230 --> 00:36:20.270 align:middle line:84%
something shifted, and
his mood went 180 degrees,

00:36:20.270 --> 00:36:22.960 align:middle line:84%
and he started giggling,
laughing, joking, playing

00:36:22.960 --> 00:36:24.230 align:middle line:90%
with the shamans.

00:36:24.230 --> 00:36:27.930 align:middle line:84%
And then in between
sessions with them,

00:36:27.930 --> 00:36:31.230 align:middle line:84%
he turned to this
boy about a year

00:36:31.230 --> 00:36:33.270 align:middle line:84%
older than him, who was
there, who turned out

00:36:33.270 --> 00:36:34.917 align:middle line:90%
was the son of our guide.

00:36:34.917 --> 00:36:36.750 align:middle line:84%
But we hadn't been
introduced at that point,

00:36:36.750 --> 00:36:38.000 align:middle line:90%
didn't know who he was.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:39.820 align:middle line:84%
And opened his arms
and hugged this boy

00:36:39.820 --> 00:36:41.870 align:middle line:90%
and said, Mongolian brother.

00:36:41.870 --> 00:36:46.600 align:middle line:84%
And he hadn't reached out
to any other child ever.

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:49.009 align:middle line:84%
He had played a bit when
other children were there

00:36:49.009 --> 00:36:50.800 align:middle line:84%
in what's called parallel
play, where he'll

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:52.850 align:middle line:90%
play while another child plays.

00:36:52.850 --> 00:36:53.650 align:middle line:90%
But no interaction.

00:36:53.650 --> 00:36:55.108 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No
engaging, no physical.

00:36:55.108 --> 00:36:56.350 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Zero.

00:36:56.350 --> 00:37:01.940 align:middle line:84%
And it happened there, and
that caused Tulga, our guide,

00:37:01.940 --> 00:37:04.720 align:middle line:84%
to say, well, maybe I
should bring Tomoo, my son,

00:37:04.720 --> 00:37:07.284 align:middle line:84%
on this journey, so it was two
fathers and their children.

00:37:07.284 --> 00:37:08.700 align:middle line:84%
And that turned
out to be the best

00:37:08.700 --> 00:37:09.866 align:middle line:90%
decision that could've been.

00:37:09.866 --> 00:37:11.750 align:middle line:84%
Now this happened in
that shamanic ceremony.

00:37:11.750 --> 00:37:13.790 align:middle line:84%
He made his first
friend, and he went

00:37:13.790 --> 00:37:16.260 align:middle line:84%
from being completely
freaked out to suddenly being

00:37:16.260 --> 00:37:19.840 align:middle line:84%
completely tickled and
giggly about the whole thing.

00:37:19.840 --> 00:37:24.120 align:middle line:84%
Something shifted, and
then it began to rain,

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:26.090 align:middle line:84%
and certain birds
flew in, all of which

00:37:26.090 --> 00:37:28.105 align:middle line:90%
are shamanic signs of blessing.

00:37:28.105 --> 00:37:29.230 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And good fortune.

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:31.730 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And good fortune,
sort of ubiquitously no matter

00:37:31.730 --> 00:37:33.730 align:middle line:90%
where you are in the world.

00:37:33.730 --> 00:37:35.740 align:middle line:84%
And then we began the
journey from there,

00:37:35.740 --> 00:37:38.800 align:middle line:84%
but I do have to say
that if I had really

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:42.530 align:middle line:84%
felt that Rowan was
in any sort of danger

00:37:42.530 --> 00:37:44.477 align:middle line:84%
or that we were be
exploited in any way,

00:37:44.477 --> 00:37:46.560 align:middle line:84%
I'd have wrapped the whole
thing up and gone home.

00:37:46.560 --> 00:37:47.360 align:middle line:90%
I'm a realist.

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:50.827 align:middle line:84%
I'm not-- there's not a
new age bone in my body.

00:37:50.827 --> 00:37:51.910 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Nor your wife's.

00:37:51.910 --> 00:37:52.230 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: No.

00:37:52.230 --> 00:37:54.562 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I have long hair,
so people think I'm-- no,

00:37:54.562 --> 00:37:57.145 align:middle line:84%
I have long hair I listened to
too much heavy metal when I was

00:37:57.145 --> 00:37:57.550 align:middle line:90%
a teenager.

00:37:57.550 --> 00:37:58.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: There you go.

00:37:58.410 --> 00:37:59.090 align:middle line:90%
Metallica, there you go.

00:37:59.090 --> 00:38:00.950 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And it's Peter
Pan syndrome, which I'm not

00:38:00.950 --> 00:38:02.300 align:middle line:90%
proud of, but there you go.

00:38:02.300 --> 00:38:07.010 align:middle line:84%
But I'm very
practical by nature.

00:38:07.010 --> 00:38:08.960 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But you were
getting enough signs

00:38:08.960 --> 00:38:11.760 align:middle line:84%
along the way and
enough validation.

00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:13.700 align:middle line:84%
But I want to bring
something up here.

00:38:13.700 --> 00:38:16.000 align:middle line:84%
You talk about in the
documentary-- they brought it

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:19.140 align:middle line:84%
up-- that these shaman, as
they were working on your son,

00:38:19.140 --> 00:38:21.510 align:middle line:84%
and I made a note
as I was watching

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:25.600 align:middle line:84%
this early on when your son
was having a tantrum at home.

00:38:25.600 --> 00:38:27.590 align:middle line:84%
I thought, god, it's
almost the little guy

00:38:27.590 --> 00:38:29.980 align:middle line:84%
has someone surfing off
him, almost like he's

00:38:29.980 --> 00:38:31.430 align:middle line:90%
acting in a possessed way.

00:38:31.430 --> 00:38:35.390 align:middle line:84%
And I say that loosely
speaking, but when

00:38:35.390 --> 00:38:37.450 align:middle line:84%
they start working on
them, they were saying,

00:38:37.450 --> 00:38:40.480 align:middle line:84%
no, there is this relative
from your wife's bloodline,

00:38:40.480 --> 00:38:41.950 align:middle line:84%
the grandmother,
I believe it is.

00:38:41.950 --> 00:38:42.750 align:middle line:90%
Who is--

00:38:42.750 --> 00:38:44.000 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Not being helpful.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:47.830 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: She was attaching
herself to your son.

00:38:47.830 --> 00:38:51.940 align:middle line:84%
And that brings up a
whole array of questions.

00:38:51.940 --> 00:38:53.540 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Certainly.

00:38:53.540 --> 00:38:54.340 align:middle line:90%
The easiest--

00:38:54.340 --> 00:38:55.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And when they
made that detachment

00:38:55.820 --> 00:38:57.528 align:middle line:84%
is when you started
seeing breakthroughs,

00:38:57.528 --> 00:38:59.546 align:middle line:84%
when they started having
the entity move on.

00:38:59.546 --> 00:39:01.170 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Yes, and
what's interesting

00:39:01.170 --> 00:39:04.040 align:middle line:84%
about the whole idea
of ancestors, which

00:39:04.040 --> 00:39:07.200 align:middle line:84%
is how shamanism works, so
the way shamanism works,

00:39:07.200 --> 00:39:09.720 align:middle line:84%
very briefly, it's very
simple how shamanism works.

00:39:09.720 --> 00:39:12.600 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't matter whether it's
Native America, the Bushmen,

00:39:12.600 --> 00:39:15.474 align:middle line:90%
the Arctic, Aboriginals.

00:39:15.474 --> 00:39:17.140 align:middle line:84%
No matter where you
are on planet Earth,

00:39:17.140 --> 00:39:19.190 align:middle line:84%
it's the same,
because this goes back

00:39:19.190 --> 00:39:21.790 align:middle line:84%
to the earliest days of what
it means to be a human being.

00:39:21.790 --> 00:39:24.530 align:middle line:84%
So when a shaman goes into the
altered state of consciousness

00:39:24.530 --> 00:39:27.030 align:middle line:84%
that they need to go
into in order to heal,

00:39:27.030 --> 00:39:28.379 align:middle line:90%
they enter the spirit world.

00:39:28.379 --> 00:39:29.920 align:middle line:84%
And when they enter
the spirit world,

00:39:29.920 --> 00:39:32.750 align:middle line:84%
they talk specifically
to ancestor spirits,

00:39:32.750 --> 00:39:34.940 align:middle line:90%
to nature spirits, and to God.

00:39:34.940 --> 00:39:39.670 align:middle line:84%
And there's a sort of a
three in one, one in three.

00:39:39.670 --> 00:39:41.686 align:middle line:84%
They sort of are each
other and not each other,

00:39:41.686 --> 00:39:43.310 align:middle line:84%
but those are the
three basic entities.

00:39:43.310 --> 00:39:45.530 align:middle line:84%
And then they come out with
a series of instructions,

00:39:45.530 --> 00:39:47.700 align:middle line:84%
and the ancestor spirits
seem almost always there

00:39:47.700 --> 00:39:48.870 align:middle line:90%
trying to help.

00:39:48.870 --> 00:39:51.840 align:middle line:84%
But occasionally,
they're getting it wrong.

00:39:51.840 --> 00:39:54.510 align:middle line:84%
So it's not that
it's malevolent.

00:39:54.510 --> 00:39:58.460 align:middle line:84%
It's more that someone
might be carrying

00:39:58.460 --> 00:40:00.750 align:middle line:84%
their human insecurities
over with them or something

00:40:00.750 --> 00:40:02.160 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:40:02.160 --> 00:40:08.410 align:middle line:84%
And by releasing this person,
this child, or whoever

00:40:08.410 --> 00:40:10.460 align:middle line:84%
from the ailment that
they're suffering,

00:40:10.460 --> 00:40:12.470 align:middle line:84%
you then release
that ancestor spirit

00:40:12.470 --> 00:40:14.770 align:middle line:84%
from what was holding
them back on it.

00:40:14.770 --> 00:40:16.640 align:middle line:90%
So it's sort of cyclical.

00:40:16.640 --> 00:40:20.850 align:middle line:84%
And this goes to the
core of the human psyche,

00:40:20.850 --> 00:40:22.950 align:middle line:84%
so much so that if
you think about it

00:40:22.950 --> 00:40:26.847 align:middle line:84%
in modern medical terms, one
person's DNA and genetics is,

00:40:26.847 --> 00:40:28.430 align:middle line:84%
of course, another
person's ancestors.

00:40:28.430 --> 00:40:31.890 align:middle line:84%
What is genetics, if not
the study of your ancestors?

00:40:31.890 --> 00:40:33.660 align:middle line:84%
So really, it's speaking
the same language

00:40:33.660 --> 00:40:34.660 align:middle line:90%
but in different motifs.

00:40:34.660 --> 00:40:36.490 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, depending on
the dimension you're looking at,

00:40:36.490 --> 00:40:38.730 align:middle line:84%
so to speak, and a
realm you're looking at,

00:40:38.730 --> 00:40:40.750 align:middle line:84%
it's the same thing
carrying for the same bonds,

00:40:40.750 --> 00:40:41.900 align:middle line:90%
the same attachments.

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:44.522 align:middle line:84%
It's in the spirit world or
through your physical DNA,

00:40:44.522 --> 00:40:45.480 align:middle line:90%
that's how it attaches.

00:40:45.480 --> 00:40:45.910 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Absolutely.

00:40:45.910 --> 00:40:47.070 align:middle line:84%
And by the way,
with that said, I

00:40:47.070 --> 00:40:48.445 align:middle line:84%
think people should
be skeptical.

00:40:48.445 --> 00:40:53.260 align:middle line:84%
I think skepticism is a
very healthy human trait.

00:40:53.260 --> 00:40:54.061 align:middle line:90%
Show me the money.

00:40:54.061 --> 00:40:56.143 align:middle line:84%
You don't want someone
coming up and saying, well,

00:40:56.143 --> 00:40:58.885 align:middle line:84%
I'm a shaman, because I went
for a two-day shamanic retreat

00:40:58.885 --> 00:40:59.760 align:middle line:90%
in Boulder, Colorado.

00:40:59.760 --> 00:40:59.970 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:40:59.970 --> 00:41:02.181 align:middle line:84%
But-- OK, now let's
move this story forward.

00:41:02.181 --> 00:41:03.430 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: And here's 10,000.

00:41:03.430 --> 00:41:05.650 align:middle line:84%
Give me 10 grand, and
I'll heal your kid.

00:41:05.650 --> 00:41:06.576 align:middle line:90%
You don't want that.

00:41:06.576 --> 00:41:08.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No, and
I'm with you on that.

00:41:08.200 --> 00:41:09.820 align:middle line:84%
The proof's in the
pudding, as they say.

00:41:09.820 --> 00:41:10.140 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Absolutely.

00:41:10.140 --> 00:41:11.860 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So you
started seeing proof.

00:41:11.860 --> 00:41:13.240 align:middle line:84%
You started seeing
a shift in him

00:41:13.240 --> 00:41:17.480 align:middle line:84%
after this ceremony in which the
grandmother's energy was asked

00:41:17.480 --> 00:41:18.564 align:middle line:90%
to please leave the child.

00:41:18.564 --> 00:41:19.396 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Exactly.

00:41:19.396 --> 00:41:21.040 align:middle line:84%
And we had to do
a sort of homework

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:23.100 align:middle line:84%
each night of certain
little ceremonies with him.

00:41:23.100 --> 00:41:24.760 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Now let's go
on to the reindeer people

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:25.560 align:middle line:90%
and what happened.

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:28.920 align:middle line:84%
Now mind you, Rowan was
how old at this time?

00:41:28.920 --> 00:41:29.720 align:middle line:90%
Three or four?

00:41:29.720 --> 00:41:29.980 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Five and a half.

00:41:29.980 --> 00:41:31.070 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Five and a half.

00:41:31.070 --> 00:41:33.370 align:middle line:90%
And he was still incontinent.

00:41:33.370 --> 00:41:34.380 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Oh, yeah.

00:41:34.380 --> 00:41:36.430 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so you
guys could not train him.

00:41:36.430 --> 00:41:38.510 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: No washing machines,
by the way, on the set.

00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:38.890 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, I know.

00:41:38.890 --> 00:41:40.082 align:middle line:90%
There's one scene in there.

00:41:40.082 --> 00:41:41.290 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, and you called it what?

00:41:41.290 --> 00:41:42.020 align:middle line:90%
The brown--

00:41:42.020 --> 00:41:42.680 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Code brown.

00:41:42.680 --> 00:41:43.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Code brown.

00:41:43.470 --> 00:41:45.053 align:middle line:84%
So you had a lot of
code browns, where

00:41:45.053 --> 00:41:46.310 align:middle line:90%
he's pooping his pants a lot.

00:41:46.310 --> 00:41:46.620 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yeah.

00:41:46.620 --> 00:41:49.090 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so this is
obvious-- any parent could

00:41:49.090 --> 00:41:51.607 align:middle line:84%
say, five and a half years
of pooping your pants-- that

00:41:51.607 --> 00:41:53.690 align:middle line:84%
would be enough for me
right there to drive me out

00:41:53.690 --> 00:41:55.300 align:middle line:90%
of my mind.

00:41:55.300 --> 00:41:57.620 align:middle line:90%
And the other stuff aside.

00:41:57.620 --> 00:42:00.035 align:middle line:84%
So this was a significant
issue in your lives,

00:42:00.035 --> 00:42:01.910 align:middle line:84%
and now let's talk about
the reindeer people.

00:42:01.910 --> 00:42:02.890 align:middle line:90%
And then what happened?

00:42:02.890 --> 00:42:03.690 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: OK.

00:42:03.690 --> 00:42:07.544 align:middle line:84%
So we eventually traveled
up to southern Siberia,

00:42:07.544 --> 00:42:09.210 align:middle line:84%
which is where the
reindeer people live.

00:42:09.210 --> 00:42:11.747 align:middle line:84%
And the reindeer people
are different to the people

00:42:11.747 --> 00:42:13.080 align:middle line:90%
of the plains, the horse people.

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:13.880 align:middle line:90%
They're older.

00:42:13.880 --> 00:42:15.090 align:middle line:90%
The culture's older.

00:42:15.090 --> 00:42:17.430 align:middle line:84%
The first large animal,
in fact, after the ice age

00:42:17.430 --> 00:42:19.320 align:middle line:84%
that was domesticated
was the reindeer.

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:22.090 align:middle line:84%
All the other ones that
we know came later.

00:42:22.090 --> 00:42:24.390 align:middle line:84%
And so it's a very,
very ancient culture

00:42:24.390 --> 00:42:26.136 align:middle line:90%
and a non-warrior culture.

00:42:26.136 --> 00:42:28.760 align:middle line:84%
Very peaceful culture, and they
live entirely off the reindeer.

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:30.290 align:middle line:90%
They ride them.

00:42:30.290 --> 00:42:31.540 align:middle line:90%
It's like going to fairyland.

00:42:31.540 --> 00:42:33.200 align:middle line:84%
It's like the land of the
snow queen when you go there.

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:33.800 align:middle line:90%
People are riding around--

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:35.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you
arrive there expecting

00:42:35.660 --> 00:42:37.660 align:middle line:84%
to meet the top--
you'd been told

00:42:37.660 --> 00:42:40.090 align:middle line:84%
you could meet the
top shaman there,

00:42:40.090 --> 00:42:41.682 align:middle line:84%
who was, I guess,
elderly or not well.

00:42:41.682 --> 00:42:42.640 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Absolutely.

00:42:42.640 --> 00:42:43.810 align:middle line:90%
A guy called Ghoste, yes.

00:42:43.810 --> 00:42:46.268 align:middle line:84%
And when you go to meet shamans,
one of the things you know

00:42:46.268 --> 00:42:47.819 align:middle line:90%
is that there's no guarantee.

00:42:47.819 --> 00:42:49.360 align:middle line:84%
I've had experience
with this before.

00:42:49.360 --> 00:42:51.818 align:middle line:84%
There's no guarantee that they
will agree to work with you.

00:42:51.818 --> 00:42:53.080 align:middle line:90%
They may not think they can.

00:42:53.080 --> 00:42:54.160 align:middle line:84%
You may not be
able to find them,

00:42:54.160 --> 00:42:55.290 align:middle line:84%
because they've
gone somewhere else,

00:42:55.290 --> 00:42:57.500 align:middle line:84%
and you've got to travel
four days on horseback

00:42:57.500 --> 00:42:59.530 align:middle line:90%
to go get them or something.

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:03.370 align:middle line:84%
Any number of things, and
so it's quite fraught.

00:43:03.370 --> 00:43:05.420 align:middle line:84%
But we did find
Ghoste, and Ghoste

00:43:05.420 --> 00:43:07.410 align:middle line:90%
did agree to work on Rowan.

00:43:07.410 --> 00:43:09.960 align:middle line:84%
And Ghoste is the name of this
healer of the reindeer people.

00:43:09.960 --> 00:43:11.240 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Can we look
at that in the film?

00:43:11.240 --> 00:43:11.630 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yeah, absolutely.

00:43:11.630 --> 00:43:13.430 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I mean,
it's really-- it's

00:43:13.430 --> 00:43:16.480 align:middle line:84%
quite a dramatic-looking
characterization

00:43:16.480 --> 00:43:19.000 align:middle line:84%
for any shaman the
way he appeared,

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:21.077 align:middle line:90%
and you were in the yurt.

00:43:21.077 --> 00:43:21.910 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: The ger.

00:43:21.910 --> 00:43:22.340 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The ger.

00:43:22.340 --> 00:43:23.630 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Well,
actually then, teepees.

00:43:23.630 --> 00:43:24.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Tee pees.

00:43:24.080 --> 00:43:25.500 align:middle line:90%
OK, so you're in the teepee.

00:43:25.500 --> 00:43:27.964 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to pick the
film up at that place, OK?

00:43:27.964 --> 00:43:30.434 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:43:30.434 --> 00:43:33.892 align:middle line:90%
[DRUMMING]

00:43:33.892 --> 00:43:39.820 align:middle line:90%


00:43:39.820 --> 00:43:46.736 align:middle line:90%
-[CHILD TALKING]

00:43:46.736 --> 00:43:47.724 align:middle line:90%
-Just sit quietly.

00:43:47.724 --> 00:43:50.194 align:middle line:90%
Sit quietly.

00:43:50.194 --> 00:43:51.182 align:middle line:90%
Sit quietly.

00:43:51.182 --> 00:43:51.676 align:middle line:90%
-Wow.

00:43:51.676 --> 00:43:52.520 align:middle line:90%
That's the shaman.

00:43:52.520 --> 00:43:53.490 align:middle line:90%
He's an eagle.

00:43:53.490 --> 00:43:58.807 align:middle line:84%
He going on the tree,
and an eagle nest.

00:43:58.807 --> 00:44:03.470 align:middle line:90%


00:44:03.470 --> 00:44:04.680 align:middle line:90%
-Drink water.

00:44:04.680 --> 00:44:06.051 align:middle line:90%
Drink the water.

00:44:06.051 --> 00:44:06.851 align:middle line:90%
[WHINING]

00:44:06.851 --> 00:44:07.825 align:middle line:90%
-Drink water.

00:44:07.825 --> 00:44:08.799 align:middle line:90%
Drink it.

00:44:08.799 --> 00:44:09.773 align:middle line:90%
Drink it.

00:44:09.773 --> 00:44:16.591 align:middle line:90%


00:44:16.591 --> 00:44:19.640 align:middle line:90%
[DRUMMING]

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:22.040 align:middle line:90%
-[CHILD TALKING]

00:44:22.040 --> 00:44:25.661 align:middle line:90%
-[NON-ENGLISH]

00:44:25.661 --> 00:44:26.910 align:middle line:90%
-He says it'd be fine if the--

00:44:26.910 --> 00:44:27.710 align:middle line:90%
-Did you see?

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:29.370 align:middle line:90%
There's a baby elk.

00:44:29.370 --> 00:44:30.385 align:middle line:90%
-[NON-ENGLISH]

00:44:30.385 --> 00:44:32.140 align:middle line:90%
-Uh-huh.

00:44:32.140 --> 00:44:35.645 align:middle line:84%
He thinks he will be
better by tomorrow.

00:44:35.645 --> 00:44:37.545 align:middle line:90%
-OK.

00:44:37.545 --> 00:44:38.500 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:44:38.500 --> 00:44:41.710 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: So what was going on
there, which is so interesting,

00:44:41.710 --> 00:44:43.930 align:middle line:84%
was there, the way
the healing turned out

00:44:43.930 --> 00:44:46.480 align:middle line:90%
was much closer to the Bushmen.

00:44:46.480 --> 00:44:49.370 align:middle line:84%
And he didn't
touch Rowan at all.

00:44:49.370 --> 00:44:50.340 align:middle line:90%
He danced.

00:44:50.340 --> 00:44:52.870 align:middle line:10%
He got himself into the state
of altered consciousness

00:44:52.870 --> 00:44:55.300 align:middle line:10%
on the drum, dancing
his way in senior.

00:44:55.300 --> 00:44:57.300 align:middle line:90%
He could do it very quickly.

00:44:57.300 --> 00:44:58.740 align:middle line:90%
And he did several things.

00:44:58.740 --> 00:45:01.761 align:middle line:84%
He offered run a small bowl
of reindeer milk, which

00:45:01.761 --> 00:45:04.010 align:middle line:84%
of course, Rowan rejected
and knocked out of his hand.

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:08.470 align:middle line:84%
And he caught it on
his drum and noted

00:45:08.470 --> 00:45:10.320 align:middle line:90%
which side it had landed on.

00:45:10.320 --> 00:45:13.330 align:middle line:84%
And then he took off
his headdress, which

00:45:13.330 --> 00:45:14.970 align:middle line:90%
is always a bird headdress.

00:45:14.970 --> 00:45:15.770 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:45:15.770 --> 00:45:18.360 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And
gave it to Rowan.

00:45:18.360 --> 00:45:21.660 align:middle line:84%
And Rowan accepted it, and
then turned around and put it

00:45:21.660 --> 00:45:24.330 align:middle line:84%
on his own head and
then put it on my head.

00:45:24.330 --> 00:45:27.050 align:middle line:84%
And at that point, Ghoste
put the drum down and said,

00:45:27.050 --> 00:45:27.890 align:middle line:90%
we're done.

00:45:27.890 --> 00:45:29.740 align:middle line:90%
And that was maybe 15 minutes.

00:45:29.740 --> 00:45:32.320 align:middle line:84%
We traveled so
long to get there.

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:33.530 align:middle line:90%
And so he lit up a cigarette.

00:45:33.530 --> 00:45:35.010 align:middle line:84%
And it's like,
OK, yeah, be cool.

00:45:35.010 --> 00:45:35.620 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: They all smoked.

00:45:35.620 --> 00:45:36.310 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Yes, of course.

00:45:36.310 --> 00:45:37.520 align:middle line:90%
They smoked, they drank.

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:38.410 align:middle line:90%
They're people.

00:45:38.410 --> 00:45:40.656 align:middle line:84%
And they chase
each other's wife.

00:45:40.656 --> 00:45:42.030 align:middle line:84%
They do the stuff
that people do.

00:45:42.030 --> 00:45:42.830 align:middle line:90%
They're not saints.

00:45:42.830 --> 00:45:44.960 align:middle line:84%
They're just people with
an affinity for healing.

00:45:44.960 --> 00:45:51.070 align:middle line:84%
And he said, OK, the stuff
that really drives you crazy--

00:45:51.070 --> 00:45:54.560 align:middle line:84%
the incontinence, the
tantruming, that stuff-- that

00:45:54.560 --> 00:45:56.140 align:middle line:90%
will all end right now.

00:45:56.140 --> 00:45:59.135 align:middle line:90%


00:45:59.135 --> 00:46:01.260 align:middle line:84%
But to confirm this
healing, you're

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:03.790 align:middle line:84%
going to have to do three more
journeys over the next three

00:46:03.790 --> 00:46:04.590 align:middle line:90%
years.

00:46:04.590 --> 00:46:06.420 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't matter where you go.

00:46:06.420 --> 00:46:07.410 align:middle line:90%
I know-- we talked.

00:46:07.410 --> 00:46:09.620 align:middle line:84%
So he says, I know you
have an African background.

00:46:09.620 --> 00:46:10.480 align:middle line:90%
I know you've got the Bushmen.

00:46:10.480 --> 00:46:11.190 align:middle line:90%
I've heard of those guys.

00:46:11.190 --> 00:46:12.140 align:middle line:84%
I know they're
very good healers.

00:46:12.140 --> 00:46:13.350 align:middle line:84%
You don't have to
come back here,

00:46:13.350 --> 00:46:14.725 align:middle line:84%
because I understand
that getting

00:46:14.725 --> 00:46:16.660 align:middle line:84%
to this mountain in
Siberia is very difficult,

00:46:16.660 --> 00:46:19.160 align:middle line:84%
and it's not really reasonable
to come back here every-- you

00:46:19.160 --> 00:46:20.620 align:middle line:90%
know, we're talking like that.

00:46:20.620 --> 00:46:21.950 align:middle line:84%
And he said, but you
are going to have to do

00:46:21.950 --> 00:46:23.260 align:middle line:90%
these three more journeys.

00:46:23.260 --> 00:46:25.177 align:middle line:84%
And I said, OK,
fine, but what do

00:46:25.177 --> 00:46:26.760 align:middle line:84%
you mean it's going
to stop right now?

00:46:26.760 --> 00:46:30.436 align:middle line:84%
Because I've been
around a lot of shamans.

00:46:30.436 --> 00:46:32.560 align:middle line:84%
They like to hedge their
bets a bit like doctors do

00:46:32.560 --> 00:46:33.560 align:middle line:90%
and accountants.

00:46:33.560 --> 00:46:37.420 align:middle line:84%
It's very rare that they'll
say, oh, it'll happen tomorrow.

00:46:37.420 --> 00:46:40.680 align:middle line:84%
But we rode back
down that mountain,

00:46:40.680 --> 00:46:46.540 align:middle line:84%
and 27 hours-- we counted it--
after leaving the reindeer

00:46:46.540 --> 00:46:50.290 align:middle line:84%
camp, Rowan did his
first intentional poo

00:46:50.290 --> 00:46:53.117 align:middle line:84%
and cleaned himself,
and it's on camera.

00:46:53.117 --> 00:46:55.450 align:middle line:84%
And for me, that was like
watching England win the World

00:46:55.450 --> 00:46:58.050 align:middle line:90%
Cup, which will never happen.

00:46:58.050 --> 00:46:59.940 align:middle line:90%
And I couldn't believe it.

00:46:59.940 --> 00:47:02.110 align:middle line:84%
And then we counted
in the two weeks

00:47:02.110 --> 00:47:06.020 align:middle line:84%
that it took to get from that
river back to Austin, Texas

00:47:06.020 --> 00:47:07.830 align:middle line:84%
where we live, because
we had to travel,

00:47:07.830 --> 00:47:10.010 align:middle line:84%
and then we went via
London, et cetera.

00:47:10.010 --> 00:47:14.000 align:middle line:84%
And we counted six
tantrums of any note.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:17.080 align:middle line:84%
Normally, that would have
been one day's worth.

00:47:17.080 --> 00:47:21.540 align:middle line:84%
So what he also left
behind him in Mongolia

00:47:21.540 --> 00:47:23.120 align:middle line:84%
was the inability
to make friends.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:25.670 align:middle line:84%
He continued to develop
the friendship with Tomoo.

00:47:25.670 --> 00:47:26.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That little boy.

00:47:26.170 --> 00:47:26.973 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And then
when he got back,

00:47:26.973 --> 00:47:29.223 align:middle line:84%
he made friends with all the
kids in the neighborhood.

00:47:29.223 --> 00:47:31.010 align:middle line:84%
So he came back-- he
went out autistic.

00:47:31.010 --> 00:47:32.342 align:middle line:90%
He came back autistic.

00:47:32.342 --> 00:47:33.300 align:middle line:90%
I looked at the camera.

00:47:33.300 --> 00:47:35.540 align:middle line:84%
I said, Rowan was
not cured of autism.

00:47:35.540 --> 00:47:37.350 align:middle line:90%
Shamanism doesn't cure autism.

00:47:37.350 --> 00:47:38.750 align:middle line:90%
Horses don't cure autism.

00:47:38.750 --> 00:47:40.360 align:middle line:90%
Nothing cures autism.

00:47:40.360 --> 00:47:42.540 align:middle line:90%
Autism is a way of being.

00:47:42.540 --> 00:47:45.050 align:middle line:84%
But there are challenges
within autism-- say,

00:47:45.050 --> 00:47:47.450 align:middle line:84%
incontinence or sensory issues
or neurological issues--

00:47:47.450 --> 00:47:48.680 align:middle line:90%
that we can address.

00:47:48.680 --> 00:47:52.430 align:middle line:84%
And they had been addressed,
and so he came back

00:47:52.430 --> 00:47:55.230 align:middle line:84%
a much, much more
functional autistic person.

00:47:55.230 --> 00:47:58.650 align:middle line:84%
And from there,
never looked back.

00:47:58.650 --> 00:48:02.770 align:middle line:84%
And we did to make those
three subsequent journeys.

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:03.779 align:middle line:90%
I wrote about them.

00:48:03.779 --> 00:48:05.570 align:middle line:84%
I have a new book that's
about to come out.

00:48:05.570 --> 00:48:06.520 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I was going
to ask you that.

00:48:06.520 --> 00:48:08.450 align:middle line:84%
Tell us what happened
after Mongolia.

00:48:08.450 --> 00:48:09.250 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: OK.

00:48:09.250 --> 00:48:11.175 align:middle line:84%
So after-- there's
this book in this film

00:48:11.175 --> 00:48:13.050 align:middle line:84%
called "The Horse Boy,"
which tells the story

00:48:13.050 --> 00:48:13.690 align:middle line:90%
through Mongolia.

00:48:13.690 --> 00:48:15.770 align:middle line:84%
Now there's a book called
"The Long Ride Home,"

00:48:15.770 --> 00:48:18.500 align:middle line:84%
and it tells the story of those
three journeys and everything

00:48:18.500 --> 00:48:21.310 align:middle line:84%
we've done subsequently
to sort of move this

00:48:21.310 --> 00:48:22.915 align:middle line:90%
into helping other kids.

00:48:22.915 --> 00:48:24.040 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: How old is Rowan?

00:48:24.040 --> 00:48:24.980 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: He's 13.

00:48:24.980 --> 00:48:28.550 align:middle line:84%
So the first journey we
did was to the Bushmen,

00:48:28.550 --> 00:48:31.670 align:middle line:84%
who I know personally, to
healers that I know personally.

00:48:31.670 --> 00:48:34.360 align:middle line:84%
And what resulted after
that, which was so bizarre,

00:48:34.360 --> 00:48:36.500 align:middle line:90%
was this mathematical dialogue.

00:48:36.500 --> 00:48:38.850 align:middle line:84%
There had been nothing
of that really.

00:48:38.850 --> 00:48:40.480 align:middle line:90%
We'd done basic numeracy.

00:48:40.480 --> 00:48:49.430 align:middle line:84%
But suddenly, Rowan was
mathematically agile, verbally,

00:48:49.430 --> 00:48:50.960 align:middle line:84%
mentally, and so
on in this way that

00:48:50.960 --> 00:48:53.540 align:middle line:84%
hadn't shown up before
when we came out of there.

00:48:53.540 --> 00:48:57.250 align:middle line:84%
The second year we
were in Australia

00:48:57.250 --> 00:48:59.840 align:middle line:84%
with a very, very
good Kuku Yalanji

00:48:59.840 --> 00:49:02.690 align:middle line:84%
shaman up in the Daintree
Rainforest, which is just

00:49:02.690 --> 00:49:06.060 align:middle line:84%
below New Guinea in that
subtropical area by Cape

00:49:06.060 --> 00:49:07.290 align:middle line:90%
Tribulation.

00:49:07.290 --> 00:49:12.010 align:middle line:84%
And after that, Rowan developed
what was called theory of mind.

00:49:12.010 --> 00:49:13.510 align:middle line:84%
I'll tell you exactly
what happened.

00:49:13.510 --> 00:49:15.090 align:middle line:84%
Theory of mind is when you
understand that I think

00:49:15.090 --> 00:49:16.430 align:middle line:90%
something different to you.

00:49:16.430 --> 00:49:17.888 align:middle line:84%
So the best way to
understand it is

00:49:17.888 --> 00:49:20.370 align:middle line:84%
let's say there was a
picture of an elephant here,

00:49:20.370 --> 00:49:22.430 align:middle line:84%
and you have a two and
1/2, three-year-old kid.

00:49:22.430 --> 00:49:23.545 align:middle line:84%
They'll pick it up
seeing the elephant

00:49:23.545 --> 00:49:25.370 align:middle line:84%
and say, hey, look,
Mommy, an elephant,

00:49:25.370 --> 00:49:27.060 align:middle line:84%
thinking that you can
see what they see.

00:49:27.060 --> 00:49:28.980 align:middle line:84%
Somewhere around three and
1/2, they'll go, hey, look,

00:49:28.980 --> 00:49:29.850 align:middle line:90%
Mommy, an elephant.

00:49:29.850 --> 00:49:31.210 align:middle line:90%
They'll turn it around.

00:49:31.210 --> 00:49:33.260 align:middle line:84%
And this is a milestone
that almost all kids

00:49:33.260 --> 00:49:35.759 align:middle line:84%
meet like speech, like pointing,
like all these other things

00:49:35.759 --> 00:49:39.410 align:middle line:84%
autistic people don't do without
you noticing it as a parent.

00:49:39.410 --> 00:49:41.330 align:middle line:84%
But of course, it's
a hard one there,

00:49:41.330 --> 00:49:43.920 align:middle line:84%
and its perspective taking
as a survival skill.

00:49:43.920 --> 00:49:45.210 align:middle line:90%
You've got to have this.

00:49:45.210 --> 00:49:47.540 align:middle line:84%
He played his first
practical joke on me

00:49:47.540 --> 00:49:52.730 align:middle line:84%
as we were driving back out
from that rainforest of--

00:49:52.730 --> 00:49:54.510 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And humor is subtle.

00:49:54.510 --> 00:49:56.292 align:middle line:84%
It's his nuanced
way of thinking.

00:49:56.292 --> 00:49:57.250 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Absolutely.

00:49:57.250 --> 00:49:59.600 align:middle line:84%
And Kristin, who's a
developmental psychology--

00:49:59.600 --> 00:50:01.387 align:middle line:84%
professor of
developmental psychology--

00:50:01.387 --> 00:50:02.220 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Your wife.

00:50:02.220 --> 00:50:03.610 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: --at the
University of Texas, his mom,

00:50:03.610 --> 00:50:04.950 align:middle line:84%
was sitting next to me
was like, oh, my god.

00:50:04.950 --> 00:50:05.910 align:middle line:90%
That's theory of mind.

00:50:05.910 --> 00:50:07.540 align:middle line:84%
I'm like, well, what do
you mean theory of mind?

00:50:07.540 --> 00:50:08.873 align:middle line:90%
I don't know the psycho speaker.

00:50:08.873 --> 00:50:10.020 align:middle line:90%
And she explained it.

00:50:10.020 --> 00:50:13.760 align:middle line:84%
And sure enough, he had
made that leap, and then

00:50:13.760 --> 00:50:16.880 align:middle line:84%
the third year, we went
on the Navajo reservation

00:50:16.880 --> 00:50:18.490 align:middle line:84%
here with a very
good Navajo shaman.

00:50:18.490 --> 00:50:20.880 align:middle line:84%
I have a bit of a background
in the Navajo reservation,

00:50:20.880 --> 00:50:24.410 align:middle line:84%
which we haven't gone into,
but I knew where to go.

00:50:24.410 --> 00:50:28.670 align:middle line:84%
And what we got after that was
proper conversation at last,

00:50:28.670 --> 00:50:30.940 align:middle line:90%
and it was incredible.

00:50:30.940 --> 00:50:34.410 align:middle line:84%
We were driving out after
the three days of ceremony,

00:50:34.410 --> 00:50:35.830 align:middle line:90%
out of the Navajo reservation.

00:50:35.830 --> 00:50:37.746 align:middle line:10%
There's Mount Taylor
hovering above the desert

00:50:37.746 --> 00:50:39.870 align:middle line:10%
like Kilimanjaro, this
sort of cloud floating

00:50:39.870 --> 00:50:41.036 align:middle line:10%
in the air above the desert.

00:50:41.036 --> 00:50:42.275 align:middle line:90%
It was so beautiful at dawn.

00:50:42.275 --> 00:50:44.400 align:middle line:84%
And, of course, because
it's America, it's prosaic.

00:50:44.400 --> 00:50:46.170 align:middle line:84%
Underneath Mount
Taylor is a truck stop,

00:50:46.170 --> 00:50:48.590 align:middle line:90%
a McDonald's, and a casino.

00:50:48.590 --> 00:50:51.150 align:middle line:10%
And we stopped between
there and Albuquerque.

00:50:51.150 --> 00:50:53.850 align:middle line:84%
We know that's where
we can get food.

00:50:53.850 --> 00:50:57.280 align:middle line:84%
So we stop, and
Rowan wants to have

00:50:57.280 --> 00:50:59.510 align:middle line:84%
one of those horrible
fruity-flavored sugary drinks

00:50:59.510 --> 00:51:01.926 align:middle line:84%
with food dyes in it, which
I know will send him squiffy.

00:51:01.926 --> 00:51:03.050 align:middle line:90%
And I wanted to have juice.

00:51:03.050 --> 00:51:04.010 align:middle line:90%
He doesn't want to have juice.

00:51:04.010 --> 00:51:05.630 align:middle line:84%
And he's like, fruity-flavored,
fruity-flavored.

00:51:05.630 --> 00:51:07.270 align:middle line:84%
He's still speaking
this sort of code

00:51:07.270 --> 00:51:09.110 align:middle line:84%
and having this massive
tantrum on the ground with all

00:51:09.110 --> 00:51:10.360 align:middle line:90%
the truckers looking at me.

00:51:10.360 --> 00:51:12.380 align:middle line:84%
Yes, I'm the hippie
parent, the bad parent.

00:51:12.380 --> 00:51:13.830 align:middle line:90%
Yes, that's me.

00:51:13.830 --> 00:51:16.974 align:middle line:84%
And we get back into
the car, and I'm grumpy.

00:51:16.974 --> 00:51:18.640 align:middle line:84%
He's grumpy, and I'm
saying, fine, fine.

00:51:18.640 --> 00:51:19.180 align:middle line:90%
Just be grumpy.

00:51:19.180 --> 00:51:20.020 align:middle line:90%
Spoil the whole day.

00:51:20.020 --> 00:51:22.730 align:middle line:90%


00:51:22.730 --> 00:51:24.580 align:middle line:84%
So I become a
three-year-old basically.

00:51:24.580 --> 00:51:26.496 align:middle line:84%
And we're driving out,
and he says to me, Dad,

00:51:26.496 --> 00:51:27.710 align:middle line:90%
I'm not being grumpy.

00:51:27.710 --> 00:51:30.920 align:middle line:84%
I'm just telling you
what drink I want.

00:51:30.920 --> 00:51:34.020 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's a different way
of handling things then, Dad.

00:51:34.020 --> 00:51:35.220 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Kristin and I,
we just pulled the car over

00:51:35.220 --> 00:51:36.594 align:middle line:84%
onto the shoulder
of the freeway,

00:51:36.594 --> 00:51:40.280 align:middle line:84%
I thought here and was
like, what did you say?

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:42.560 align:middle line:84%
And it never went
back from there.

00:51:42.560 --> 00:51:47.490 align:middle line:84%
So what happened was we
realized that the shamans thing

00:51:47.490 --> 00:51:49.560 align:middle line:84%
and the horse thing was
very personal to us,

00:51:49.560 --> 00:51:55.830 align:middle line:84%
but what we had discovered was
that if you observe your child,

00:51:55.830 --> 00:51:58.190 align:middle line:84%
and if you put your
child in nature,

00:51:58.190 --> 00:52:00.620 align:middle line:84%
and if you allow your child
to move in certain ways,

00:52:00.620 --> 00:52:02.290 align:middle line:84%
and this is why I
go back to the lope

00:52:02.290 --> 00:52:04.090 align:middle line:84%
and these rhythmic
movements on the horse.

00:52:04.090 --> 00:52:06.759 align:middle line:84%
You could emulate a lot of
these results we were getting

00:52:06.759 --> 00:52:08.550 align:middle line:84%
with Rowan without the
kids, and the reason

00:52:08.550 --> 00:52:11.890 align:middle line:84%
I knew this was when we go back
from Mongolia, I got curious.

00:52:11.890 --> 00:52:14.900 align:middle line:84%
Was it just my son, or
was it other kids too?

00:52:14.900 --> 00:52:17.330 align:middle line:84%
We now have one child in
68 over the age of eight

00:52:17.330 --> 00:52:20.850 align:middle line:84%
with autism, one boy in 56 over
the age of eight with autism.

00:52:20.850 --> 00:52:23.770 align:middle line:84%
So it's not difficult to
find other autistic kids.

00:52:23.770 --> 00:52:26.760 align:middle line:84%
So I started running unofficial
play dates with the horses,

00:52:26.760 --> 00:52:29.010 align:middle line:84%
and also, on play equipment,
because most of the time,

00:52:29.010 --> 00:52:29.820 align:middle line:90%
they weren't on the horse.

00:52:29.820 --> 00:52:32.040 align:middle line:84%
And I noticed it was
certain types of movement.

00:52:32.040 --> 00:52:32.360 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That swings.

00:52:32.360 --> 00:52:33.480 align:middle line:90%
I mean, OK.

00:52:33.480 --> 00:52:34.610 align:middle line:90%
There you go.

00:52:34.610 --> 00:52:37.100 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: And we eventually
took this to the neurologists

00:52:37.100 --> 00:52:38.760 align:middle line:90%
and said, what's going on?

00:52:38.760 --> 00:52:42.600 align:middle line:84%
And they said, ah, look at the
way the hips are being rocked.

00:52:42.600 --> 00:52:44.310 align:middle line:90%
This is oxytocin.

00:52:44.310 --> 00:52:47.620 align:middle line:84%
You're creating enormous
amounts of oxytocin in the kids.

00:52:47.620 --> 00:52:48.890 align:middle line:90%
What's oxytocin?

00:52:48.890 --> 00:52:51.196 align:middle line:84%
The bliss, happiness,
communication, trust--

00:52:51.196 --> 00:52:52.320 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Bonding chemical.

00:52:52.320 --> 00:52:55.560 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: --and
communication hormone.

00:52:55.560 --> 00:53:00.620 align:middle line:84%
And basically, what we'd lucked
into was a discovery of this.

00:53:00.620 --> 00:53:03.074 align:middle line:84%
The basic problem with
autism, if that's the brain,

00:53:03.074 --> 00:53:03.990 align:middle line:90%
there's your amygdala.

00:53:03.990 --> 00:53:06.955 align:middle line:84%
The amygdala is what
governs your fight, flight,

00:53:06.955 --> 00:53:10.540 align:middle line:84%
and freeze response and produces
cortisol, your stress hormone.

00:53:10.540 --> 00:53:14.300 align:middle line:84%
Many FMRI scans on autistic
people-- for example,

00:53:14.300 --> 00:53:18.640 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Temple Grandin has
gone in for an FMRI scan

00:53:18.640 --> 00:53:20.240 align:middle line:84%
as part of this
experiment-- show

00:53:20.240 --> 00:53:23.430 align:middle line:84%
that a lot of autistic people
have overdeveloped amygdalas.

00:53:23.430 --> 00:53:25.410 align:middle line:84%
That part of their
brain is way more

00:53:25.410 --> 00:53:27.540 align:middle line:84%
developed than yours
or mine, perhaps.

00:53:27.540 --> 00:53:30.040 align:middle line:84%
So they're suffering from much
more anxiety, much more fear,

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:32.320 align:middle line:84%
et cetera, producing
much more cortisol.

00:53:32.320 --> 00:53:35.870 align:middle line:84%
Then you've got the nervous
system is being triggered

00:53:35.870 --> 00:53:38.190 align:middle line:90%
to give misinformation.

00:53:38.190 --> 00:53:39.952 align:middle line:84%
So the easiest
way I can give you

00:53:39.952 --> 00:53:41.910 align:middle line:84%
to get you to understand
that is if you'll just

00:53:41.910 --> 00:53:43.147 align:middle line:90%
humor me for second.

00:53:43.147 --> 00:53:45.230 align:middle line:84%
Lick your finger, and wave
it around for a second.

00:53:45.230 --> 00:53:47.630 align:middle line:90%
Can you do that?

00:53:47.630 --> 00:53:48.822 align:middle line:90%
Does it feel hot or cold?

00:53:48.822 --> 00:53:49.180 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Cold.

00:53:49.180 --> 00:53:49.840 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Right.

00:53:49.840 --> 00:53:50.640 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:53:50.640 --> 00:53:53.310 align:middle line:84%
Because as the water evaporates
from your epidermis--

00:53:53.310 --> 00:53:55.110 align:middle line:84%
but you're getting the
correct information.

00:53:55.110 --> 00:53:56.320 align:middle line:90%
But imagine if you didn't.

00:53:56.320 --> 00:53:58.834 align:middle line:84%
Imagine if for that moment,
someone flipped a wrong switch,

00:53:58.834 --> 00:54:00.750 align:middle line:84%
and it suddenly felt
like I'd held your finger

00:54:00.750 --> 00:54:02.150 align:middle line:90%
to the hot burner of the stove.

00:54:02.150 --> 00:54:03.100 align:middle line:90%
How would you react?

00:54:03.100 --> 00:54:04.230 align:middle line:90%
You'd melt down.

00:54:04.230 --> 00:54:05.570 align:middle line:90%
You'd fall to the ground.

00:54:05.570 --> 00:54:06.370 align:middle line:90%
You'd scream.

00:54:06.370 --> 00:54:08.150 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You'd be overly
reactive all the time.

00:54:08.150 --> 00:54:09.890 align:middle line:84%
>>ISAACSON: Yes, and
the gents in white coats

00:54:09.890 --> 00:54:11.890 align:middle line:84%
would be along to cart
you off to the funny farm

00:54:11.890 --> 00:54:13.050 align:middle line:90%
and pump you full of drugs.

00:54:13.050 --> 00:54:15.850 align:middle line:84%
So this is what's going on
for these kids all the time.

00:54:15.850 --> 00:54:18.100 align:middle line:10%
By putting them into
this form of movement

00:54:18.100 --> 00:54:21.110 align:middle line:10%
in natural environment when
none of these bad sensory

00:54:21.110 --> 00:54:24.620 align:middle line:10%
triggers like fluorescent strip
lights, like echoey spaces,

00:54:24.620 --> 00:54:28.340 align:middle line:10%
like industrial noise, like the
hum of a refrigerator or an air

00:54:28.340 --> 00:54:31.070 align:middle line:10%
conditioner, like a yappy
dog, like cigarette smoke,

00:54:31.070 --> 00:54:33.510 align:middle line:10%
like perfume, like a million
of these things which

00:54:33.510 --> 00:54:35.890 align:middle line:10%
could set them off into
this negative cycle

00:54:35.890 --> 00:54:38.580 align:middle line:10%
between this overdeveloped
amygdala and this misfiring

00:54:38.580 --> 00:54:41.430 align:middle line:10%
nervous system, you take
those triggers away,

00:54:41.430 --> 00:54:45.400 align:middle line:10%
and you start filling them
with the opposite of cortisol.

00:54:45.400 --> 00:54:47.040 align:middle line:90%
Oxytocin-- it's the antidote.

00:54:47.040 --> 00:54:49.950 align:middle line:84%
What cortisol does is
it narrows your focus.

00:54:49.950 --> 00:54:52.680 align:middle line:84%
If a bloke came through the
wall there with a kitchen knife,

00:54:52.680 --> 00:54:54.100 align:middle line:84%
you couldn't be learning
about horse work.

00:54:54.100 --> 00:54:55.170 align:middle line:90%
You could deal with the bloke.

00:54:55.170 --> 00:54:56.890 align:middle line:84%
You're not going to learn
calculus while the elephant is

00:54:56.890 --> 00:54:57.690 align:middle line:90%
charging at you.

00:54:57.690 --> 00:54:59.310 align:middle line:84%
It narrows your
focus on the threat.

00:54:59.310 --> 00:55:01.160 align:middle line:84%
So if your brain is
constantly telling you

00:55:01.160 --> 00:55:02.800 align:middle line:84%
that there's an elephant
coming through the wall,

00:55:02.800 --> 00:55:04.880 align:middle line:84%
you haven't got time
to learn anything else.

00:55:04.880 --> 00:55:05.970 align:middle line:84%
Nothing to do with
your intellect.

00:55:05.970 --> 00:55:06.740 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Very
narrow-minded focus.

00:55:06.740 --> 00:55:07.573 align:middle line:90%
>>ISAACSON: Exactly.

00:55:07.573 --> 00:55:11.040 align:middle line:84%
Your intellect is capable of it,
but the hormones won't let it.

00:55:11.040 --> 00:55:14.980 align:middle line:10%
So what oxytocin does is it
gives you perspective focus.

00:55:14.980 --> 00:55:18.242 align:middle line:84%
It's like, hm, maybe I do
want to go to India next year.

00:55:18.242 --> 00:55:19.700 align:middle line:84%
I've always wanted
to learn French,

00:55:19.700 --> 00:55:21.626 align:middle line:90%
or I wonder what's over there.

00:55:21.626 --> 00:55:22.822 align:middle line:90%
That's that frame of mind.

00:55:22.822 --> 00:55:24.530 align:middle line:84%
So you put the kid in
that frame of mind,

00:55:24.530 --> 00:55:28.194 align:middle line:84%
but then three more
amazing things happened.

00:55:28.194 --> 00:55:30.110 align:middle line:84%
With this kind of rocking
and bouncing motion,

00:55:30.110 --> 00:55:31.940 align:middle line:90%
your cerebellum is activated.

00:55:31.940 --> 00:55:34.710 align:middle line:84%
Your cerebellum produces--
if you can remember this,

00:55:34.710 --> 00:55:37.760 align:middle line:84%
I'll give you a gold star--
the cerebellum produces

00:55:37.760 --> 00:55:41.070 align:middle line:84%
a series of cells within the
brain with a funny name called

00:55:41.070 --> 00:55:42.460 align:middle line:90%
Purkinje cells.

00:55:42.460 --> 00:55:44.680 align:middle line:84%
Purkinje cells act as
circuits within the brain that

00:55:44.680 --> 00:55:47.220 align:middle line:84%
get the different parts of your
brain to talk to each other.

00:55:47.220 --> 00:55:48.020 align:middle line:90%
Guess what.

00:55:48.020 --> 00:55:50.790 align:middle line:84%
In autistic people,
frequently, they

00:55:50.790 --> 00:55:52.970 align:middle line:84%
have a real deficit
of Purkinje cells.

00:55:52.970 --> 00:55:55.977 align:middle line:10%
So you get massive development
of this part of the brain,

00:55:55.977 --> 00:55:58.060 align:middle line:10%
not so much development
in that part of the brain.

00:55:58.060 --> 00:56:01.560 align:middle line:84%
And suddenly, you're
dealing with that problem.

00:56:01.560 --> 00:56:05.740 align:middle line:84%
And one of the bits of the brain
that the Purkinje cells allow

00:56:05.740 --> 00:56:09.450 align:middle line:84%
to talk to the rest of the
brain is the prefrontal cortex.

00:56:09.450 --> 00:56:11.700 align:middle line:84%
And the prefrontal
cortex is the CEO.

00:56:11.700 --> 00:56:15.940 align:middle line:84%
It's what governs reason
and emotional regulation.

00:56:15.940 --> 00:56:18.830 align:middle line:84%
And so suddenly, these
kids are learning

00:56:18.830 --> 00:56:22.110 align:middle line:84%
and able to control their
emotions and able to reason

00:56:22.110 --> 00:56:25.280 align:middle line:84%
and so on, and finally,
through the Purkinje cells,

00:56:25.280 --> 00:56:27.880 align:middle line:84%
the prefrontal cortex can
talk to the amygdala and say,

00:56:27.880 --> 00:56:28.680 align:middle line:90%
you know what?

00:56:28.680 --> 00:56:30.445 align:middle line:84%
There isn't an
elephant coming out

00:56:30.445 --> 00:56:32.160 align:middle line:90%
of the bush every five seconds.

00:56:32.160 --> 00:56:33.300 align:middle line:90%
So you can relax.

00:56:33.300 --> 00:56:35.660 align:middle line:84%
And so then you create
a positive cycle.

00:56:35.660 --> 00:56:38.660 align:middle line:84%
So we opened a center,
where we train people

00:56:38.660 --> 00:56:40.930 align:middle line:84%
how to do this with horses,
with play equipment.

00:56:40.930 --> 00:56:44.410 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I was going to
say those little swings that

00:56:44.410 --> 00:56:45.350 align:middle line:90%
rock automatically.

00:56:45.350 --> 00:56:48.540 align:middle line:10%
>>ISAACSON: Yes, the Gaiam
balls that you sit on,

00:56:48.540 --> 00:56:50.170 align:middle line:10%
the Gaiam exercise balls.

00:56:50.170 --> 00:56:51.360 align:middle line:90%
I'll plug your product.

00:56:51.360 --> 00:56:52.810 align:middle line:90%
No, absolutely.

00:56:52.810 --> 00:56:56.100 align:middle line:84%
So if the kid is in the back
of the class rocking his chair,

00:56:56.100 --> 00:56:58.780 align:middle line:84%
it should not have the chalk
rubber thrown at his head

00:56:58.780 --> 00:56:59.684 align:middle line:90%
or be sent outside.

00:56:59.684 --> 00:57:01.350 align:middle line:84%
He's doing what he
needs to do to learn.

00:57:01.350 --> 00:57:02.650 align:middle line:90%
He's creating oxytocin.

00:57:02.650 --> 00:57:06.140 align:middle line:84%
And when you see an
autistic person rocking,

00:57:06.140 --> 00:57:09.510 align:middle line:84%
they always rock creating
oxytocin to self-soothe.

00:57:09.510 --> 00:57:11.764 align:middle line:84%
If you and I meet each
other, and we're all friends,

00:57:11.764 --> 00:57:12.930 align:middle line:90%
we'll give each other a hug.

00:57:12.930 --> 00:57:15.920 align:middle line:84%
That will get some oxytocin, but
if you are having a hard time,

00:57:15.920 --> 00:57:18.470 align:middle line:84%
and I want to comfort
you, I will rock you.

00:57:18.470 --> 00:57:20.200 align:middle line:84%
If I have my baby in
my arms, I rock him.

00:57:20.200 --> 00:57:21.429 align:middle line:90%
It's hard wired.

00:57:21.429 --> 00:57:23.720 align:middle line:84%
And all the things that we
do where our hips are rocked

00:57:23.720 --> 00:57:27.130 align:middle line:84%
make us feel globally
a sense of well-being.

00:57:27.130 --> 00:57:28.894 align:middle line:84%
So rocking chairs,
dance, making love.

00:57:28.894 --> 00:57:30.310 align:middle line:84%
When you make love,
you don't just

00:57:30.310 --> 00:57:32.810 align:middle line:84%
feel a localized pleasure
in your genitals.

00:57:32.810 --> 00:57:34.810 align:middle line:84%
We hope, anyway, that you
feel this global sense

00:57:34.810 --> 00:57:35.410 align:middle line:90%
of well-being.

00:57:35.410 --> 00:57:36.210 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:57:36.210 --> 00:57:38.210 align:middle line:90%
It's the oxytocin at work.

00:57:38.210 --> 00:57:41.040 align:middle line:10%
So we had lucked into something
very simple and very profound

00:57:41.040 --> 00:57:43.564 align:middle line:10%
that could work massively
with the horses,

00:57:43.564 --> 00:57:45.230 align:middle line:10%
because the movement
of the horse's hips

00:57:45.230 --> 00:57:48.280 align:middle line:10%
is so powerful that it gives
you more oxytocin for your buck

00:57:48.280 --> 00:57:49.440 align:middle line:10%
than anything else.

00:57:49.440 --> 00:57:52.060 align:middle line:84%
But most people aren't on
horseback 90% of the time.

00:57:52.060 --> 00:57:53.030 align:middle line:90%
But what about a swing?

00:57:53.030 --> 00:57:53.950 align:middle line:90%
What about the pool?

00:57:53.950 --> 00:57:54.950 align:middle line:90%
What about a trampoline?

00:57:54.950 --> 00:57:55.950 align:middle line:90%
What about my shoulders?

00:57:55.950 --> 00:57:56.920 align:middle line:90%
What about a wheelbarrow?

00:57:56.920 --> 00:57:59.110 align:middle line:84%
What about all sorts of
ways that we could do this?

00:57:59.110 --> 00:58:02.560 align:middle line:84%
So we now have three programs,
and we have Horse Boy Method

00:58:02.560 --> 00:58:05.490 align:middle line:84%
with horses, which is a
therapeutic riding program that

00:58:05.490 --> 00:58:07.590 align:middle line:84%
is now in 11 countries,
and it's just

00:58:07.590 --> 00:58:11.140 align:middle line:84%
been adopted in Germany
as the official autism

00:58:11.140 --> 00:58:15.006 align:middle line:90%
treatment with equine therapy.

00:58:15.006 --> 00:58:16.380 align:middle line:84%
We have Horse Boy
Learning, which

00:58:16.380 --> 00:58:18.470 align:middle line:84%
is a home school program, a
kinetic learning home school

00:58:18.470 --> 00:58:20.749 align:middle line:84%
program, where we put the
child in nature in all these

00:58:20.749 --> 00:58:22.290 align:middle line:84%
rocking balancing
things, and then we

00:58:22.290 --> 00:58:24.880 align:middle line:84%
show them how to learn the
national curriculum this way.

